1. Nf3{ Welcome to the rich and exciting world of the Reti Opening! Named after the great Richard Reti }{ (1889-1929) }{ , the Hungarian theorist and world-class player who inflicted on Capablanca his first defeat in eight years in New York, 1924, the Reti Opening allows White to mix creativity with control from an early stage, while taking many black players out of their comfort zone which is another reason for preferring it to 1.  d4 . }( { As you would expect from an opening honed during the Hypermodern period, White is often content after  1. Nf3  to control the centre from the flanks. In this first part of a two-course complete repertoire with   }1.Nf3 { we'll examine }1...d5 2.c4 { , }{ which will often be followed up by at least two more of the typical Reti early pawn moves,  e2 - e3 ,  b2 - b3  }{ (or even  b2-b4 ) }{ , and  g2 - g3 . } )( { Along the way, we'll encounter a number of dynamic positions and often see White fighting for an initiative from an early stage, but where the play does become extremely chaotic, we've usually aimed to suggest a simpler and much more positional alternative.  Part two  of the course will complete the repertoire as we meet }1.Nf3 Nf6 { also with }2.c4 { followed by Reti-type play.    Ideally, you'll find this a fun repertoire, as well as one more than thorough enough for even the more theoretically-inclined club, tournament and online player! We've highlighted in the text where we come up against Black's better options and some other repertoire suggestions. Do also keep an eye on the highlighted squares and arrows on the board, as well as the commentary to White's moves, to see what our opponents are up to. } )( { Good luck with   }1.Nf3 d5 2.c4 { and we do hope that you will enjoy your adventures with the Reti Opening.     Richard Palliser  } )
