1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. Nf6
3. cxd5
3. Nxd5
4. e4{ Seizing space and with tempo as we prepare to boss the centre. }
4. Nb6
5. d4{ Constructing an ideal centre and just where is Black's counterplay? }
5. Bg4
6. Be3{ Keeping  d4  secure as we angle to tempt Black's queen's knight forwards. }
6. Nc6
7. d5{ The point of White's play, as we exploit our strong centre to go up a gear and seize the initiative. }
7. Ne5
8. Qd4{ Forcing the pace and a strong pawn sacrifice. Do just observe Black's potential issues on the  a4 - e8  diagonal. }
8. Nxf3+
9. gxf3
9. Bxf3
10. Bb5+{ Forcing the knight backwards. }
10. Nd7
11. Rg1{ With Black rather tied down to the defence of  g7 , just how will he ever manage to untangle his kingside?     Our coverage in the 2... Nf6  lines  }{ shows that's a hard question to answer! While Black suffers an opening disaster, White is all set to expand with  Nd2  and  f2 - f4 , with superb compensation.     In short, we should be delighted whenever Black neglects to advance his d-pawn or cover it with another pawn after 2.  c4 . }
