1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4{ A critical response to Black's most critical line. White seizes space in Benko and Blumenfeld-type vein and is now ready to lay siege to the  d4 -pawn with  Bb2 . }
3. c5
4. Bb2{ Keeping up the pressure on  d4 , a point which we'd be delighted to exchange  b4  for then enjoy a very handy central majority. }
4. a5
5. bxc5{ It's rarely bad to take a pawn when doing so comes with a threat, here to  d4 . }
5. Nc6
6. e3{ This is a key pawn break in the 2... d4  3.  b4  variation, challenging the bridgehead on  d4  and angling to open up the long diagonal for what would then be a very fine dark-squared bishop on  b2 . }
6. e5
7. Nxe5{ A piece sacrifice! White actually isn't risking too much as we'll obtain three strong pawns and the initiative. }
7. Nxe5
8. exd4{ With tempo and just look at that imposing advanced white centre, one which serves, for instance, to rather restrict the bishop on  f8 . }
8. Bg4
9. Qb3{ Not only eyeing  b7 , but preparing to swing across a rather nice post on  e3 . }
9. Nc6
10. h3{ Kicking the bishop before swinging the queen across the third rank and now Black is well advised to look for a way to return the extra piece. }
10. Bf5
11. Qe3+
11. Be7
12. d5{ Both our dark-squared bishop and powerful centre are very much making their presence felt, and there's always  Na3  to cover  c2  if needed. White enjoys very dangerous compensation, as we'll see in the 3... c5  / 4... a5  lines.  }
