3. b4{ A critical response to Black's most critical line. White seizes space in Benko and Blumenfeld-type vein and is now ready to lay siege to the  d4 -pawn with  Bb2 . }
3. c5
4. Bb2{ Keeping up the pressure on  d4 , a point which we'd be delighted to exchange  b4  for then enjoy a very handy central majority. }
4. Nf6
5. g3{ A reversed Benko-type policy, as we prepare to develop the kingside with  Bg2  and  O-O . Now that Black has loosened his queenside defences with ... c5 , the light-squared bishop will stand especially well on  g2 , gazing down towards  b7 . }
5. a5
6. b5{ Seizing space and our standard method of reacting to ... a5  in these lines. White will now complete kingside development ( Bg2  and  O-O ), take control of  e4  after  d2 - d3  and  Nbd2 , and may then play to hit back in the centre with  e2 - e3 . }
6. Nbd7
7. Bg2
7. e5
8. O-O( { White's lead in development is actually fairly useful, not least if Black can be provoked into }8...e4 9.Ng5 { . } )
8. Bd6
9. d3{ Taking control of  e4  as our light-squared bishop begins to look very well placed indeed on the long diagonal. }
9. O-O
10. a4{ White is in no rush, so rules out any potentially annoying ... a4  advance from Black before involving the final minor piece with  Nbd2 . }
10. Ra7
11. Nbd2
11. Re8
12. e3{ Countering in the centre before Black can fully untangle his pieces.     One decent plan now for White is to look to expand on the kingside while opening up the gaze of the bishop on  g2  with  Nh4 , as we'll see in the 4... Nf6  lines.  }
