4. h3{ A useful counter to Black's bold early aggression.     White simply ensures that ... g4  won't cause serious difficulties while refusing to accept the early gambit and allow Black dangerous compensation. }
4. h6
5. g3{ Despite the presence of a pawn on  g5 , White's king should be fairly safe on  g1 , in large part thanks to the defensive strength of the fianchettoed light-squared bishop. }
5. Bg7
6. d3{ Prudently ruling out any issues to do with ... d3 . }
6. e5
7. Bg2
7. Ne7
8. O-O{ Having made the king safe, White will involve the queen's knight on  d2  and may then look to make good use of our fine light-squared bishop's gaze towards the black queenside by thematically expanding on the queenside with  a2 - a4 - a5 , as we'll see in the 3...  g5  lines.  }
