3. e3( { A decent positional alternative to }3.e4 { , one which you may prefer depending on style and taste. } )
3. e6
4. Bxc4
4. c5
5. b3{ A simple and decent, Duda-inspired push. White refuses to enter the main lines of the QGA, preferring to place his dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal after all. }
5. Nf6
6. Bb2( { This position can easily also arise from both   }3...e6 4.Bxc4 { and }{   }3...c5 4.Bxc4 { move orders, as will be explored in the 3... e6  & 3...  c5  lines. White enjoys harmonious development and is now all set to house the king. } )
6. a6
7. O-O
7. Be7
8. Be2{ A prophylactic device, retreating the bishop before its attacked. White has two main plans in this structure: reversed Sicilian development with  d2 - d3  and  Nbd2 ; a quick  d2 - d4 , aiming to exploit White's small lead in development. }
8. Nc6
9. d4
9. cxd4
10. Nxd4{ White doesn't mind knights and queens coming off on  d4 , as he plays for  Bf3  and a long-term, Catalan-style edge with the better bishops, as we'll see in the 3... e6  & ... Nf6  lines.  }
