1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3{ Just as we will against the Slav, it makes sense to take control of the  d4  point.     Also, just as we'll carry out against 2... c6 , our main concept is now to fianchetto the queen's bishop after  Nc3  with  b2 - b3 . }
3. g6
4. d4{ Changing approach, clamping down on the  e5 - and  c5 -squares in the process, now that Black wants to have a bishop of his own on the long diagonal. }
4. Bg7
5. Nc3
5. Ne7
6. Be2{ Outwardly modest development, but White has a small but pleasant edge here.  O-O  will follow and then a good way to involve the queenside pieces will be  b2 - b3 ,  Ba3  (fighting against the ... c5  break), and  Rc1 . }
