1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3{ Just as we will against the Slav, it makes sense to take control of the  d4  point.     Also, just as we'll carry out against 2... c6 , our main concept is now to fianchetto the queen's bishop after  Nc3  with  b2 - b3 . }
3. c5
4. cxd5{ We'll usually meet ... c5  with this exchange, aiming to ultimately leave Black with a slightly weak pawn on  d5  after a subsequent  d2 - d4  and exchange on  c5  or  d4 . }
4. exd5
5. d4
5. Nf6
6. Bb5+{ Developing a tempo and while we have transposed from the Reti into a line of the Tarrasch Defence, White should not be too unhappy with that.     We should be able to retain control over the position and inflict an isolated queen's pawn on Black. }
6. Nbd7
7. dxc5{ With Black's queenside development a little hindered, it makes sense here to saddle him with an IQP without delay and to... }
7. a6
8. Be2{ ... Retain an important bishop. White will now continue in thematic fashion by castling and fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop. }
8. Nxc5
9. O-O
9. Be7
10. b3{ Consistent play.  Bb2  and  Nc3  will follow and while Black is fairly solid in these lines with a knight on  c5 , he does struggle slightly to obtain counterplay. }
10. O-O
11. Bb2
11. Bf5
12. Nc3{ This keeps the knight on  f6  tied down to defence of  d5 , thereby leaving White with slightly the easier position to play. Next up will be  Rc1 , as we'll see in the 3... c5  lines.  }
