1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. Nf6
3. cxd5{ Naturally we carry out the positional threat to exchange and now Black faces a sub-optimal choice: recapture and allow White to dominate the centre or sacrifice a pawn for insufficient compensation.     Usually in practice he recaptures with the knight. }
3. Nxd5
4. e4( { White's most aggressive option and one which in practice has often led to him obtaining a perfect centre.    This advance also takes advantage of the move order, unlike }4.d4 { , }{ which transposes to a position which usually arises after }{   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 Nf6?! 3.cxd5 Nxd5 4.Nf3! { . That is also considered rather pleasant for White and you may prefer it if it's also in your repertoire. } )
4. Nb6
5. d4( { Constructing the aforementioned perfect centre and only now by countering against  d4  with }5...Bg4 { can Black hope to avoid emerging clearly worse from the opening. } )
5. g6
6. h3{ This useful prophylactic device is by no means forced just yet, but it makes sense to rule out any annoying ... Bg4  ideas for good before continuing development with  Nc3  and  Be3 .     Note too how Black simply has an inferior version of a Grünfeld, having had his knight force back to  b6 , since there wasn't a white knight on  c3  to trade-off. }
6. Bg7
7. Nc3
7. O-O
8. Be3{ White already holds a very pleasant advantage.  Qd2  and  Rd1  may follow, as well as just  Be2  and  O-O . }( { Observe too how meeting }8...Nc6 { with }9.Bb5 { should inconvenience Black and that }8...c5?! 9.dxc5 { just wins a pawn. Neither is the mirror pawn break of that one to fear: } )
8. f5
9. exf5{ Simple chess. White is taking on an isolated queen's pawn, but is also preparing to annoy Black on the  a2 - g8  diagonal having first cut out any ideas of ... f4 . }
9. Bxf5
10. Qb3+
10. Kh8
11. Rd1{ Not the only good move, but it makes sense to overprotect  d4 , Markus-Purgar, Ptuj 2008.     White also adds support to any future  d4 - d5  advance, while very much preparing  Ng5 , all the while as Black continues to struggle for counterplay and should be clearly worse. }
