11. Rg1{ White's lead in development and space advantage supplies fantastic compensation for the pawn.     It clearly won't be at all easy for Black to untangle and next move  Nd2  will come with tempo. White will then have ideas of not just  e4 - e5  and  Ne4 , but even  Rxg7 . }( { Black can counter such ideas, but only in rather ugly fashion. For example: }11...a6 12.Ba4 { Needless to say White prioritises an important bishop. }12...b5 13.Bb3 { Nd2 is still very much on the way and the light-squared bishop now makes it harder for Black to contemplate any ideas of ... e6  (or ... e5  when White will capture en passant). }13...f6 14.Nd2 Bh5 15.f4 { White's powerful centre remains the dominant feature of the position. He can still look to squash Black with  e4 - e5  and may also involve the queen's rook, such as with  Rc1 - c6 , while the king seems quite safe on  e1  for the time being. } )
