3. e6( { Out of all Black's third moves, only   }3...Nf6 { is ever really seen at GM level, but we should still know how to deal with Black's lesser options, including }{   }3...b6 { when }4.Bb2 { (hitting  d4 ) }4...c5 5.e3 { transposes into the realm of the 3... c5  lines , as does }{   }3...Bf5 4.Bb2 c5 5.e3 { . We will take a look at the third move sidelines with some independent value in this chapter. } )
4. Bb2{ As we've known since at least the time of Richard Reti and his fellow Hypermoderns, exchanging a wing pawn for a central one is generally a good idea. }( { Here Black is probably best advised to avoid the swap with }4...c5 { when we'll see }5.e3 { in the 3... c5  lines.  } )
4. Bxb4
5. Nxd4{ White's extra centre pawn gives him a pleasant long-term advantage and already there is a bigger threat than just  Nc2 , namely  Qa4 +, one which even some fairly strong players have been known to miss at blitz. }
5. Be7
6. e3
6. Nf6( 6...c5 { doesn't bother us, when we continue with }7.Nb3 { and later  Be2 ,  O-O ,  Nc3  and slowly play for  d4 . } )
7. f4{ Bird-like, Larsenesque or just typical Hypermodern play depending on which term you prefer. White clamps down on  e5  ahead of his knight being kicked back to  f3 .  Nc3 ,  Be2 ,  O-O  and  Qc2  will then complete development, after which White might play to gradually roll forwards in the centre and/or look for a kingside attack after getting  Ne5  in. }
