[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4{ The aim here is to fianchetto on  b2  quickly, adding pressure to Black's center which we will claim is overextended. And in many lines we don't mind trading our b-pawn for Black's central pawn, which they've spent more tempi on. }
3. e5
4. Nxe5{ Pocketing a pawn which Black has usually just blundered, only spotting now that the pawn on  b4  is taboo due to a certain check.     In any case White might now throw  Qa4 + to slightly discombobulate and  Bb2  is also on its way, with Black reduced to scrambling around for some compensation. }
4. Qf6
5. Qa4+( { An important check and improvement on the only move tested so far over the board (OTB), namely }5.Nd3 { . Now White would love, if allowed, to pocket the bishop-pair on  d7  and otherwise can safely retreat the knight back to  f3 . } )
5. c6
6. Nf3{ White is now all set to go  Bb2  and need not fear Black pushing on: }
6. d3
7. Nc3{ Without the insertion of 5.  Qa4 +  c6 , Black would be able to take on  b4  here, but now everything is secure. }
7. Bg4
8. Bb2{ White can still hope that a generous opponent might take on  e2  and so allow 9.  Bxe2  followed by  O-O  to complete development.     In any case, it won't be too long before White can get on with kingside development, since here a very strong plan is  Nd1 - e3 , unfurling the fianchettoed bishop, hitting the one on  g4  and plugging the e-file. }
