1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4{ The aim here is to fianchetto on  b2  quickly, adding pressure to Black's center which we will claim is overextended. And in many lines we don't mind trading our b-pawn for Black's central pawn, which they've spent more tempi on. }
3. Nc6
4. b5
4. Na5
5. d3{ Black's sidelined knight creates a strange impression and now 6.  Bd2  is arguably even more of an issue for him than just 6.  Bb2 . }
5. c5
6. g3{ A switch from our usual  e3  policy, but a good choice here. The bishop will take up a fine role on the long, light-squared diagonal and Black may now find it much harder to recycle his knight with ... b6  and ... Nb7 . }
6. g6
7. Bg2
7. Bg7
8. O-O{ Safely housing the king ahead of preparing to target the knight on the rim with  Bd2 . }
8. a6
9. a4{ Maintaining White's bind and an open a-file isn't especially going to help Black or his stricken knight. }
9. Nf6
10. Ra3{ This wasn't necessary just yet, but is a very useful move to cover  b3 , thereby allowing White to follow up  Bd2  with  Qe1 . Black was already in some trouble here in Kjartansson-Adamczyk, Pardubice 2021, with White easily able to target the resulting weakness on  a5 . }( { It's worth seeing just a few more moves where the Icelandic Grandmaster carried out his plan to perfection: }10...Ra7 11.Bd2 Nd7 12.Qe1! { Phase one complete and now Black is forced into a rather ugly pawn advance. }12...b6 13.Bxa5 bxa5 14.Nbd2 { With  Nb3  on its way, Black quickly found himself a clear pawn down for no compensation. } )
