2. d4
3. b4{ The aim here is to fianchetto on  b2  quickly, adding pressure to Black's center which we will claim is overextended. And in many lines we don't mind trading our b-pawn for Black's central pawn, which they've spent more tempi on. }
3. g5
4. h3{ Remaining calm and making ... g4  somewhat less appealing to Black. We rather like this restrained choice, hoping to argue that sooner or later Black's Grob-like kingside may remain weak. }( { White most certainly should avoid }4.Nxg5?! e5 { when both the knight and  b4  hang, and even }{   }4.Bb2 Bg7 5.Nxg5 e5 { has been shown to give Black promising compensation. } )
4. Bg7
5. Nxg5{ It's time to be brave and bag the pawn, since ... e5  will no longer carry a double attack. Also, we haven't committed our dark-squared bishop to  b2 , something which may well prove useful. }
5. e5
6. d3( { Taking control of  e4  and not }6.Ne4? f5 { . } )
6. h6
7. Nf3{ The right way to retreat, again not allowing ... f5  to come with tempo. }
7. f5
8. Nbd2( { Taking control of  e4  and now Black is likely to fight for that square, although we'll see }8...Ne7 9.g3 { in the illustrative game Palliser-Carroll, 4NCL 2023.  } )
8. Qe7
9. g3( { Stronger than the }9.Nb3?! { of Matsenko-Baltag, Konya 2017, as White boldly ignores both of Black's ideas: } )
9. Qxb4
10. Bg2
10. Nc6
11. O-O{ White's lead in development is a substantial one and he is about to seize the initiative.  Rb1  will apply indirect pressure to  b7  and once the black queen retreats, White may follow up with  Qa4  and  Ba3 .     Another important idea is  Nh4 , eyeing the weakened black kingside, while opening up the potentially powerful bishop on  g2  and allowing White to contemplate  e2 - e3  ideas, intending a certain check on  h5 . }
