3. b4{ The aim here is to fianchetto on  b2  quickly, adding pressure to Black's center which we will claim is overextended. And in many lines we don't mind trading our b-pawn for Black's central pawn, which they've spent more tempi on. }
3. Bg4
4. g3{ Provoking Black to carry out his main idea and exchange on  f3 . In any case, our light-squared bishop is again heading to  g2  and the king should be fairly safe on  g1 . }( { Of the many alternatives, }4.Qb3 { has been by far White's main move and is likely what Black will be most expecting. It's a pretty decent move, but the queen can prove slightly vulnerable to ... a5 - a4 . } )( { Of the alternatives, there just isn't a decent follow-up to }4.Ne5 Bf5 ( { and }4.Bb2 Bxf3 5.exf3 e5 { is a little too comfortable for Black. } ) )
4. f6
5. h3{ Forcing the issue. Now the insertion of  h3  is likely to be a fairly useful extra move should the bishop retreat. }
5. Bxf3
6. exf3
6. e5
7. a3( { Holding the queenside together. }7.Qb3 { might appear more natural, but then }7...Nd7 { followed by ... a5  is slightly awkward to meet. } )
7. a5
8. bxa5( { A change of approach. }8.b5 { is far from terrible, but here the  h1 - a8  diagonal isn't open and  f3 - f4  not so easy to force through if Black sits with a bishop on  d6 . } )
8. Nd7
9. d3{ Usefully ruling out any notion of ... d3  ahead of developing the kingside. }
9. Bd6
10. Bg2
10. Ne7
11. O-O{ Mission accomplished and now we should hope that Black will recapture on  a5  (doing so earlier could well lead to the same position). }
11. Rxa5
12. Nd2{ Now  Ne4  followed by  Nxd6  and  f3 - f4  to open the position for White's bishops is the plan and prevention not without risk for Black: }
12. f5
13. Nb3
13. Ra7
14. f4{ Ripping open lines, unfurling the bishop on  g2  and, of course, White would be delighted to swap  f4  for a huge knight on  d4 . }
