1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4{ We'll now moving on to examining Black's major options against our uncompromising  b2 - b4  advance and begin by looking at what happens when Black both overprotects  d4  and prepares to capture on  b4 . }
3. c5
4. Bb2( { White's most popular choice, simply intending  bxc5  while being quite happy to swap  b4  for  d4 . Instead, }4.bxc5?! Nc6 5.e3 e5 { is rather too comfortable for Black, but }4.e3 { is possible and if you don't mind a reversed Benko theme then both }4.g3 { , }{ as once played by Aronian against Carlsen, and }4.b5!? { are fully viable too. } )( { After }4.Bb2 { , }{ Black's most important option is }4...Nf6 { , }{ but in practice a whole array of other moves have also been seen. } )( { We'll focus on:   }4...a5 ( {   }4...Nf6  )( { Do, though, also make sure that on top of spotting that   }4...cxb4?! 5.Nxd4 { would be a favourable trade, you have some grasp of how to counter Black's various other possibilities. } ) )
4. g6
5. e3{ This doesn't look like the best version of the 3... g6  lines for Black, who is able to hang on to  d4 , but will have to spend some time in regaining his pawn on  c5 . }
5. Bg7
6. bxc5
6. Nc6
7. Na3{ Preserving the tension while heading for  b5  or  c2 .     To avoid drifting into early trouble Black must now find an equally creative route into play for his remaining knight. }
7. Nh6
8. Nb5
8. Bg4
9. Be2{ Breaking the pin without delay to place  d4  back under attack. }
9. Nf5
10. Nbxd4( { This is old theory, but decent theory }{ ( }10.Qc1!? { and }10.Qb3 { should also promise White an edge).     In short, while Black is regaining his pawn after mass exchanges, White should be able to secure some sort of target or asset. } )
10. Bxf3
11. Bxf3{ A more straightforward option than taking on  f5 . }
11. Nfxd4
12. exd4
12. Bxd4
13. Rb1{ Defending the bishop and beginning to suggest that  b7  could become vulnerable. }
13. O-O
14. O-O
14. Bxc5
15. Bxc6
15. bxc6
16. d4{ White's mobile pawn centre and menacing bishop behind it leave him slightly but definitely for choice. Black will always have to be on his guard on the long, dark-square diagonal, as well as on  e7 , with White able to activate his queen via  g4 . }
