10. h3( { An important little move to toss in, forcing Black to make a decision over his bishop, or at least }10.Qe3+ Be7 11.d5 Nb4 12.Na3 Kf8 { doesn't seem so clear to us.     We would be quite happy taking White after 10.  h3  and it looks like there are good chances to emerge with an advantage, although it should be said that Robert Ris didn't seem so unhappy with Black after 9... Nc6  on his DVD,  A Complete Black Repertoire Against 1.Nf3 & 1.c4 . } )
10. Nxd4
11. Qe3+{ Black can't save both pieces, but it should be noted that this is how the engines want to try and defend after 10.  h3 . }
11. Ne6
12. hxg4
12. Bxc5
13. Qb3{ Here to reduce the impact of any ... Qb6  ideas and this position could really do with a test - or three. Black's hold on  d4  clearly gives him some compensation, but it may not be quite enough.     White is not only ready to go  Nc3 - d5 , but also has ideas of  Qxb7  and  Qc6 +, as well as just  Qb5 +, but do be very careful with any  Bxg7  tricks as they may run into a powerful rejoinder in the shape of ... Qe7  followed by a discovered check. }
