[White "3) Reversed Benoni: The Natural 3...c5"]
[Black "Reversed Benoni: 4...a5 #6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4
3. c5
4. Bb2( { White's most popular choice, simply intending  bxc5  while being quite happy to swap  b4  for  d4 . Instead, }4.bxc5?! Nc6 5.e3 e5 { is rather too comfortable for Black, but }4.e3 { is possible and if you don't mind a reversed Benko theme then both }4.g3 { , }{ as once played by Aronian against Carlsen, and }4.b5!? { are fully viable too. } )( { After }4.Bb2 { , }{ Black's most important option is }4...Nf6 { , }{ but in practice a whole array of other moves have also been seen. } )( { We'll focus on:   }4...a5 ( {   }4...Nf6  )( { Do, though, also make sure that on top of spotting that   }4...cxb4?! 5.Nxd4 { would be a favourable trade, you have some grasp of how to counter Black's various other possibilities. } ) )
4. a5
5. bxc5( { Thanks to the inclusion of  Bb2  and  ...a5 , this is now well-timed, in contrast to which }5.b5 { would give Black an improved version of the 3... a5  lines, as we've played  Bb2  instead of  e2 - e3 . } )
5. Nc6
6. e3{ Thematically continuing to undermine the black pawn chain and now Black really must support  d4 . }( { Instead, }6...dxe3? 7.fxe3 { would leave White still a pawn to the good, with a dominant centre and also a rather useful bishop on  b2 . } )
6. e5
7. Nxe5( { A bold, but engine-approved piece sacrifice.    In return we not only jolt Black a large shock, but obtain a powerful pawn centre and full compensation, in contrast to which }7.exd4 exd4 8.d3 Bxc5 { wouldn't make great use of the bishop on  b2 . We will present an alternative though for those users too timid to take on  e5 , but you really should do so as it offers White good chances of emerging with a large early advantage. } )
7. Nxe5
8. exd4{ With tempo and now White also has ideas of a timely  d4 - d5  advance, with Black's most ambitious and likely best response seen in the only OTB test of 7.  Nxe5  which we've been able to find. }
8. Bg4
9. Qb3( { The best square for the queen, pressuring  b7  and with the option of swinging across to  e3  White must also make absolutely sure that he isn't cleaned up by }9.f3?? Nxf3+! 10.gxf3 Qh4+ 11.Ke2 Bxf3+! { . } )
9. Nc6
10. h3( { An important little move to toss in, forcing Black to make a decision over his bishop, or at least }10.Qe3+ Be7 11.d5 Nb4 12.Na3 Kf8 { doesn't seem so clear to us.     We would be quite happy taking White after 10.  h3  and it looks like there are good chances to emerge with an advantage, although it should be said that Robert Ris didn't seem so unhappy with Black after 9... Nc6  on his DVD,  A Complete Black Repertoire Against 1.Nf3 & 1.c4 . } )
10. Bf5
11. Qe3+{ Now this is well-timed, with  d4 - d5  to follow or just  Be2  and  O-O . }
11. Be7
12. d5
12. Nb4
13. Na3{ This simple defence, ruling out any accidents, reveals why White was happy to force the pace with 12.  d5 . }
13. Kf8
14. Be2{ We can now appreciated why White flicked in 10.  h3 . Black can no longer swap this bishop off, leaving him suffering as White castles short then prepares to roll the d-pawns. }
