10. a4{ White elects to lock the queenside and rule out any notion of ... a4  before challenging in the centre with  e2 - e3  and  Nbd2 . }( { There's time to do this with Black not up to much ( }10.e3 { and 11.  Nbd2  is also fine if you prefer). } )
10. Ra7
11. Nbd2
11. Re8
12. e3{ Increasing the central tension so certainly keeps Black on his toes and having to assess the impact of any exchange on  d4  every move. }
12. b6
13. Nh4{ A strong manoeuvre, which introduced the idea of  Bc6  in So-Anand, Bucharest (rapid) 2019.     White might follow that up with  Qf3  and probing on the light squares or, as So did, closing the centre with  e3 - e4  ahead of arranging  f2 - f4  and pressing forwards on the kingside. Black is still pretty solid and may be OK, but Anand did find himself coming under serious pressure once White got  f2 - f4  in. }
