1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4
3. g6
4. g3( { White's most popular move here has actually been }4.Bb2 { , }{ but by fianchettoing on the kingside without delay and leaving the bishop on  c1 , we gain a few more options, such as a timely  Ba3 .    Black's set-up is designed to overprotect  d4  and expand in the centre and }{   }4.Bb2 Bg7 5.e3 e5 { is absolutely fine for him, so we won't rush with the  e2 - e3  break. } )( { After }4.g3 { Black usually continues his own fianchetto, although }4...a5 5.b5 { and a transposition to the realm of the 3... a5  lines  is also possible. } )
4. Bg7
5. Bg2{ Not for the first time we're happy to tempt Black forwards in the centre, as well as with }( 5...a5 6.b5 { and another transposition back into the 3... a5  lines.  } )
5. Nf6
6. O-O{ Continuing our kingside first approach ahead of targeting  d4 . }
6. O-O
7. Bb2( { Now there's a simple threat of  Bxd4  and as we saw back in the  3... c5  lines, }7...c5 8.d3 { leaves White slightly for choice with  Nbd2 - b3  on the way in conjunction with  bxc5 . } )
7. Ne8
8. d3{ Black players have unsurprisingly so far avoided this position, since it's not clear what positive role the knight fulfils on  e8 .     White will continue with  Nbd2  and then begin to seize further space with  a2 - a4 , while after ... e5  it will always be possible too to very much consider the  e2 - e3  break. }
