3. b4
3. g6
4. g3( { White's most popular move here has actually been }4.Bb2 { , }{ but by fianchettoing on the kingside without delay and leaving the bishop on  c1 , we gain a few more options, such as a timely  Ba3 .    Black's set-up is designed to overprotect  d4  and expand in the centre and }{   }4.Bb2 Bg7 5.e3 e5 { is absolutely fine for him, so we won't rush with the  e2 - e3  break. } )( { After }4.g3 { Black usually continues his own fianchetto, although }4...a5 5.b5 { and a transposition to the realm of the 3... a5  lines  is also possible. } )
4. Bg7
5. Bg2{ Not for the first time we're happy to tempt Black forwards in the centre, as well as with }( 5...a5 6.b5 { and another transposition back into the 3... a5  lines.  } )
5. e5
6. d3( { Simple chess, clearing  d2  for the queen's knight, while not allowing Black any fun after }6.O-O e4 7.Ne1 { , }{ which actually isn't so clear. } )
6. Ne7
7. O-O
7. O-O
8. Nbd2( { Simple chess, developing a piece and giving White the handy option of  Nb3 , although we must admit that we were torn for a while between this move and the immediate }8.a4!? { . }{ Now though  9.a4  is very much our aim, followed by storming the queenside, if allowed. } )( { This position has been known since at least the 1950s and in practice Black's most common reaction by some margin has been to try and keep the queenside relatively closed with }8...a5 { . As such we'll examine alternatives to 8... a5  now. } )
8. Nd7
9. a4
9. Rb8
10. b5{ With Black having prudently removed his rook from the gaze of our fine bishop on  g2 , we should be happy to keep gaining space, with  Ba3  and  a4 - a5  now set to follow. }
10. b6
11. a5{ Levering open lines and activating the rook. }
11. Bb7
12. axb6
12. axb6
13. Ra7{ White is set to go  Ba3  and  Qa1 , and should have a small but definite edge. }( { The only time that this position has been reached, Black tried too hard to be creative: }13...c5? 14.Nxe5! Bxg2 15.Rxd7 { Exploiting the downside to 13... c5 . White will either now recapture on  g2  and go  Ra7 , with an extra pawn, or enjoy favourable simplification. }15...Bxf1?! 16.Rxd8 Rbxd8 17.Nxf7! Rxf7 18.Qxf1 Ra8 19.Qg2! { White enjoys a large advantage and went on to grind out the win in Franco Alonso-Magem Badals, Spanish Team Championship, Monzon 2016.     Qe4  and  Kg2  may follow or just  Ne4 - g5  and meanwhile the tactics favour White. }19...Ra1?! 20.Nb3 Rb1? 21.Qa8+ { Black is losing the exchange. } )
