11. Nxd4{ It's more important to remove the bridgehead than the supporting pawn on  e5 . If Black sensibly declines, White will drop the knight back to  f3  then improve the dark-squared bishop with  Bb2 .     After that, gradually arranging  e2 - e3  and  d3 - d4  is one plan, manoeuvring to break with  f2 - f4  another and  Ne4 - c3 - d5  could also prove useful at some point. }
11. exd4
12. Bxa8{ The bishop isn't getting trapped, meaning White is an exchange and a pawn to the good. We should now aim to keep Black devoid of counterplay while improving our pieces, as with  Bg2 ,  Nf3  and then gradually arranging to break and open lines with  e2 - e3 . }
