8. Nbd2( { Simple chess, developing a piece and giving White the handy option of  Nb3 , although we must admit that we were torn for a while between this move and the immediate }8.a4!? { . }{ Now though  9.a4  is very much our aim, followed by storming the queenside, if allowed. } )( { This position has been known since at least the 1950s and in practice Black's most common reaction by some margin has been to try and keep the queenside relatively closed with }8...a5 { . As such we'll examine alternatives to 8... a5  now. } )
8. a5
9. b5( { Seizing space and keeping the pawn chain intact. Practice has shown that White hasn't anything special after }9.bxa5 Nec6 10.Nb3 Nxa5 11.Nxa5 Rxa5 { , }{ so instead he prepares to carry on expanding on the queenside with  Nb3 ,  a2 - a4  (a useful enough move to avoid any issues with a timely ... a4 ), and  Ba3 . } )
9. c5
10. Ba3( { This is likely to surprise a well-prepared opponent, as White has almost overwhelming preferred }10.bxc6 { in practice when a tough manoeuvring struggle ensues after the likes of }10...Nexc6! 11.Rb1 Na6 12.Ne1 { .     The immediate attack on  c5  is, however, engine-approved and not for the first time we'll see that defending  c5  while aiming to catch up in development isn't so easy for Black. } )
10. Qb6
11. e3( { Breaking without delay. White actually now threatens to win a pawn after   }12.exd4 exd4 13.Nb3 { . } )
11. dxe3
12. fxe3
12. Bf5
13. e4( { Straightforward play, although }13.Qe2!? { is also tempting, intending to give up the exchange on  a1  for all the dark squares with }13...e4 14.Nxe4 { . } )
13. Bg4
14. h3{ Despite the closed nature of the position and weaknesses on the d-file, White is slightly but definitely for choice whether or not Black exchanges on  f3 .     We'll recapture there with the knight is needed, and in any case  Qe2 , to cover  d3 , and  Bb2 , to tie Black down to  e5 , are on their way. White then has a few plans to increase the pressure, including  Rf2  and  Raf1 ,  h3 - h4  and  Bh3  (especially if Black has swapped on  f3 ; if not  Ng5  might trouble the bishop on  e6 ), and even  Ne1 - c2 - e3 . }
