[White "5) Reversed Benoni: The Ambitious 3…f6 - 5th Moves"]
[Black "Reversed Benoni: 4...dxe3 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4{ We now move on to Black's main theoretical and most popular response, one which sees him aiming to build a powerful pawn centre. It's also a line which was recommended in both 'Beating Unusual Chess Openings' and Viktor Mikhalevski's more recent 'Beating Minor Openings', as well as in Daniel Barrish and Christof Sielecki's course 'Lifetime Repertoires: Nimzo-Ragozin'. }
3. f6
4. e3{ White has tried a wide range of alternatives, but we're happy to stick with the main line, immediately undermining  d4 . In a related Sämisch type position there would already be a pawn on  c4  (c5 in reverse), but here the  c5 -square currently belongs to White. }( { As Black loses a pawn after }4...d3? 5.Qb3 Bf5 6.Nh4 { , }{ he normally now elects to shore up  d4  by advancing the e-pawn. That is, of course, logical, but Black's light squares are a little weak and he is potentially vulnerable down the  a2 - g8  diagonal. } )
4. dxe3
5. fxe3
5. e5
6. c5{ The most dangerous move for Black to face, hemming in his dark-squared bishop while opening the  a2 - g8  diagonal and intending  Bc4 . }( { If you find this a little too avant-garde, }6.Qb3 { is also a decent choice, as is another space-gainer in }6.b5!? { . } )
6. Bg4
7. Bc4( { Simple chess, focusing on the long diagonal and provoking the move Black thought he was threatening in  7...e4.  }7.Qb3 { and }7.Bb2 { are also rather good for White. } )
7. e4
8. Qc2{ The point. Black's bishop on  g4  is loose as we once again see him regretting having gone ... f6 .     White threatens both to take on  e4  and go  Nd4 . }
8. exf3
9. Qe4+
9. Ne7
10. Qxg4
10. fxg2
11. Qxg2( { White enjoyed much the more active pieces and a large advantage with Black's light squares shot in Ingbrandt-Landgren, Swedish League 2014. After the natural }11...Nbc6 { we can temporarily sac the pawn with }12.O-O { and have a big initiative. Black's main problem is the king in the center. } )
