4. e5
5. c5{ We'll begin our examination of this fascinating advance and variation by examining what happens if Black counters with an equally ambitious advance of his own, one that Richard recommended several years ago in 'Beating Unusual Chess Openings'. }( { White has tested a range of alternatives }{ ( }5.Nxe5? fxe5 6.Qh5+ Ke7 { leads nowhere, but }{   }5.b5!? { can be considered if you like your space and a manoeuvring struggle), but this is the main line and most critical try, again aiming to cause Black early and significant problems down the weakened  a2 - g8  diagonal.     Now Black usually challenges immediately on the queenside, but one can certainly imagine an opponent either not au fait with the theory or scared by White's aggression preferring something else to 5... a5 . } )( {   }5....b6 { trying to undermine the  c5  pawn fails to }6.Bc4 { simply developing, with some  Nxe5  tactics in the air. }{    We'll now divide our coverage between: }( { - Alternatives to }5...a5  )( { - The Critical   }5...a5  )( 5...dxe3 { is covered by transposition under }{   }4....dxe3 { 5 }fxe3 { - variations 1 to 10 of this chapter. } ) )
5. Bg4
6. h3{ Kicking the bishop proves useful ahead of occupying the  a2 - g8  diagonal. }
6. Bxf3
7. Qxf3
7. Nc6
8. a3{ Securing the queenside ahead of bringing the unopposed light-squared bishop into play. }
8. Qd7
9. Bc4{ Carsten Hansen assessed this as an edge for White, but it might even be more than that. After all, where will the black king find safety? It's not about to go short and would surely prefer not to castle long into a pawn storm.     Meanwhile White will go  O-O  then most likely complete development with  d2 - d3 ,  Nd2  and  Bb2 , possibly followed by ganging up on  d4  with  Nb3 . }
