*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Reversed Benoni: The Ambitious 3…f6 - 5th Moves"]
[Black "Reversed Benoni: 4...e5 (Alternative - 4.d3 #1)"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4{ We now move on to Black's main theoretical and most popular response, one which sees him aiming to build a powerful pawn centre. It's also a line which was recommended in both 'Beating Unusual Chess Openings' and Viktor Mikhalevski's more recent 'Beating Minor Openings', as well as in Daniel Barrish and Christof Sielecki's course 'Lifetime Repertoires: Nimzo-Ragozin'. }
3. f6
4. d3{ White takes control of  e4  and also rules out any notion of ... d3 . }
4. e5
5. a3{ Securing  b4 . Only now is White ready to hit back in the centre and challenge  d4  with  e2 - e3 . Black has two critical responses, countering vigorously on the queenside. }
5. c5
6. b5{ White has rarely closed lines here, but the space-gaining advance ... b4  is known in the Benko and it can't be so bad here either. White would like to follow up with  g2 - g3  and  Bg2 , placing his bishop on a pretty fine diagonal. }
6. Bd6
7. g3
7. f5
8. Bg2( { Much simpler than the }8.Bh3 { of Schrader-Wrede, correspondence 2003, as the black e-pawn will now quickly become vulnerable if it advances. } )
8. Nf6
9. O-O{ With the king safe, White is now in a position to hit back with  e2 - e3  or just to continue annexing space with  a4 - a5 . }
9. e4
10. dxe4
10. fxe4
11. Nh4{ An unstereotyped but fairly strong reaction to Black's ambitious central advance. White simply wants to go after  e4  with  Bg5  then  Nbd2 , while also being aware that any ...  Nbd7  may walk into  Nf5 . }
