[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4{ We now move on to Black's main theoretical and most popular response, one which sees him aiming to build a powerful pawn centre. It's also a line which was recommended in both 'Beating Unusual Chess Openings' and Viktor Mikhalevski's more recent 'Beating Minor Openings', as well as in Daniel Barrish and Christof Sielecki's course 'Lifetime Repertoires: Nimzo-Ragozin'. }
3. f6
4. d3{ White takes control of  e4  and also rules out any notion of ... d3 . }
4. e5
5. a3{ Securing  b4 . Only now is White ready to hit back in the centre and challenge  d4  with  e2 - e3 . Black has two critical responses, countering vigorously on the queenside. }
5. a5
6. b5{ Keeping lines closed in our standard fashion from the 3... a5  lines, as well as White's options open with all of  e2 - e3 ,  g2 - g3  and  a3 - a4  potential follow-ups.     Of these the  e2 - e3  break is likely to be the most challenging, since after  g2 - g3  Black should be able to obtain a fairly comfortable game by bringing his queen's knight to a fine spot with ... Nd7 - c5 . }
6. Nd7
7. e3
7. dxe3
8. fxe3{ The dynamic recapture. White will likely continue development with  Be2 ,  O-O  and  Nc3 , while looking to advance and take over the centre with a timely  d3 - d4 . }
8. e4
9. Nd4{ Minimising the damage to White's structure while threatening  Ne6 . }
9. Nc5
10. Nc3{ Only now is White happy to accept doubled e-pawns as he plans to exchange off Black's active knight with  Nxe4 . }
10. exd3
11. Bxd3{ This menaced  Qh5 + and also left White all set to castle, with a lead in development and perhaps slightly the better chances in a rather positionally complex scenario, G. Henderson-Roebuck, correspondence 2017. }
