5. a3{ Securing  b4 . Only now is White ready to hit back in the centre and challenge  d4  with  e2 - e3 . Black has two critical responses, countering vigorously on the queenside. }
5. a5
6. b5{ Keeping lines closed in our standard fashion from the 3... a5  lines, as well as White's options open with all of  e2 - e3 ,  g2 - g3  and  a3 - a4  potential follow-ups.     Of these the  e2 - e3  break is likely to be the most challenging, since after  g2 - g3  Black should be able to obtain a fairly comfortable game by bringing his queen's knight to a fine spot with ... Nd7 - c5 . }
6. Ne7
7. e3{ Forcing Black into a non-straightforward decision: to hold  d4  or not? }
7. Nf5
8. g4( { Taking up the challenge against Mikhalevski's suggestion. This is tempting and likely stronger than the also quite playable and more conventional }8.exd4 Nxd4 9.Nxd4 Qxd4 10.Ra2 { followed by  Be3 . } )
8. Ne7
9. Rg1{ Covering  g4  so left White slightly for choice in Marciz-Cornel, correspondence 2020. We'd also argue that White has a fair degree of control, with  Nd2 - e4  very possible, as well as ideas of a timely and undermining  g4 - g5  or  h2 - h4 - h5 . }
