[White "6) Reversed Benoni: The Ambitious 3…f6 - 5…a5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Reversed Benoni: 6...Nc6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4
3. f6
4. e3
4. e5
5. c5
5. a5
6. Qa4+{ White's main move these days, disrupting Black's development, pinning the a-pawn, and preparing both  b4 - b5  and to sacrifice the  c5 -pawn. }( { Of the alternatives, we can't recommend }6.exd4? e4! { or }{   }6.Nxe5? fxe5 7.Qh5+ Ke7! { , }{ but }{   }6.Bb2!? { is Stockfish-approved, if yet to receive an over-the-board test. After }6...dxe3 7.fxe3 axb4 8.d4 { White definitely has some compensation and this has led to two draws so far in correspondence play. } )( { Following the queen check, Black usually blocks with the bishop. That is by no means forced, although of the alternatives   }6...Nd7? { would be especially welcomed by White as }7.exd4 exd4 8.Nxd4 { is just an extra pawn.      We now have a further divide: }( 6...Qd7  )( 6...Bd7  ){ These variations both lead to some extremely rich and fun positions, but before enjoyably exploring them, we should check two other ways that Black has been known to block the check. } )
6. Nc6
7. b5{ Forcing the pace. With  d4  also under pressure, Black pretty much must head forwards. }
7. Nb4
8. a3{ With both of Black's bishops threatening to powerfully jump into the fray, the active knight should be kicked backwards. }
8. Nd5
9. exd4( { Simple chess, although Adrien Demuth's }9.Qc2!? { may also give White an edge. } )( { After the text, }9...e4?! 10.Ng1! { followed by  Bc4 ,  Nbc3  and  Nge2  shouldn't give Black anything like enough for a pawn, so he should prefer to recapture. } )
9. exd4
10. Qxd4{ Naturally pocketing the pawn with  c5  set to fall in any case. }
10. Qe7+
11. Be2
11. Qxc5
12. Qb2{ A new idea, as for once it's the queen, not bishop, which goes here. White keeps queens on, frees  d4  for the knight or pawn, and still wants to attack down the e-file after  O-O  and  Re1 . }( { Instead, }12.O-O Qxd4 13.Nxd4 Bc5 { was Demuth-So, French Team Championship 2015, when Tony Kosten's idea of }14.Nb3 Bd6 15.Nc3 { should be a little better for White. } )
12. Nf4
13. d4( { The knight will fall after }13...Nxg2+ 14.Kf1 { and defending it doesn't especially help Black: } )
13. Qf5
14. Bxf4
14. Qxf4
15. O-O{ With  Re1  on the way, not to mention  Bc4  and  Nc3 , Black will do very well to get out of the early middlegame alive. }
