[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4
3. f6
4. e3
4. e5
5. c5
5. a5
6. Qa4+{ White's main move these days, disrupting Black's development, pinning the a-pawn, and preparing both  b4 - b5  and to sacrifice the  c5 -pawn. }( { Of the alternatives, we can't recommend }6.exd4? e4! { or }{   }6.Nxe5? fxe5 7.Qh5+ Ke7! { , }{ but }{   }6.Bb2!? { is Stockfish-approved, if yet to receive an over-the-board test. After }6...dxe3 7.fxe3 axb4 8.d4 { White definitely has some compensation and this has led to two draws so far in correspondence play. } )( { Following the queen check, Black usually blocks with the bishop. That is by no means forced, although of the alternatives   }6...Nd7? { would be especially welcomed by White as }7.exd4 exd4 8.Nxd4 { is just an extra pawn.      We now have a further divide: }( 6...Qd7  )( 6...Bd7  ){ These variations both lead to some extremely rich and fun positions, but before enjoyably exploring them, we should check two other ways that Black has been known to block the check. } )
6. c6
7. Bc4{ With ... axb4  off the agenda for now, it makes sense to bring the light-squared bishop to its best post. White is now very much able to consider ideas of  Qb3  after all, as well as just  O-O  and  Bb2 , increasing the pressure on  d4 .     It may also be possible to go  b4 - b5 , aiming to seize an early initiative by pressuring  c6 , or just  a2 - a3  to secure the queenside. }
7. Na6
8. a3{ Securing  b4 , preparing  Bb2 , as well as  O-O , and also intending a queen sacrifice! }
8. Ne7
9. O-O{ Continuing to dangle the queen before Black. }
9. axb4
10. axb4
10. Nc7
11. Qxa8
11. Nxa8
12. Rxa8{ This position was tested in two blitz games in 2021 between Jeffery Xiong and Wesley So, no less.     We rather like White's lead in development and the engines agree that he should be doing fairly well with  exd4  and  Bb2  on the way. }
12. g5
13. Bb2( { Deviating from Xiong's }13.exd4 { . Now that capture is definitely a threat as Black is rather provoked into going all in on the kingside. } )
13. g4
14. Nh4( { A strong leap as White threatens   }15.exd4 exd4 16.Re1 { and 17.  Be6 . } )
14. Ng6
15. Nxg6
15. hxg6
16. exd4{ Black's centre is collapsing and, worry not, matters are under control if he slightly desperately tries to play for mate: }
16. Qd7
17. dxe5{ Continuing to eat pawns while also opening up the e-file. }
17. Qh7
18. h3
18. gxh3
19. g3{ The star resource, if not an uncommon motif in general. Now White will always be able to meet ... h2 + with  Kh1 , using the black pawn as cover, and there's always  f2 - f3  if needed to cover the light squares. }{ Meanwhile  Rxc8 + and  exf6  are both threatened, and the engines consider White's advantage to be almost '+2'! }
