14. Qh1+
15. Ke2{ Playing for the win and now White threatens both the bishop and to trap the black queen with  Nc3  and  Bb2 . }
15. cxb5
16. Qxb5+( { Continuing to spurn the bishop while hoping that Black will allow his queen to become trapped after }16...Nd7? 17.Nc3 { . } )( { Instead, }16.Qxc5 Na6 17.Qxb5+ Bd7 { shortly fizzled out to an endgame where Black's rook and pawn were the equal of the two white knights in a battle between two 2560s, Murray-D'Adamo, correspondence 2017. } )( {   }16...Nc6 17.Nc3 Bg4! 18.Qxc5 { By now there's nothing better. Does Black have enough for the piece or might he even fail to notice the neat threat of 19.  Qxf8 +? }18...Bxf3+ 19.Rxf3 Qxh2+ 20.Rf2 { Forcing the pace ahead of trying to escape with the king. }20...Qh5+ 21.Ke1 Qh1+ 22.Rf1 { No draw, thank you! }22...Qh4+ 23.Kd1 Qg4+ 24.Ne2! { The king seems as safe on  d1  as anywhere and White is now finally able to complete development with  Ba3  and  Rc1  or  Rb1 .     With both kings far from ideally placed, matters are still far from clear, but with White also having  Rg1  ideas, we'd slightly prefer to be in his shoes and aim to gradually turn the extra piece into an attacking asset. } )
