15. Nc3{ We've sacrificed as many as three pawns, but are ready to begin regaining them with  O-O-O  then  Nxe4 . It's also still far from easy for Black to untangle as dragging a white knight to  b5  is unlikely to help him. The latest engines definitely prefer White and he has scored a whopping 4.5/5 in correspondence testing. }( { For example:     A.  }15...Ne7 ( {  B.  }15...c5? 16.O-O-O Ne7 17.Rf4! { This stunning piece sacrifice already pretty much spelt the end for the black king in Claridge-Schrancz, correspondence 2014, where Black only lasted another four moves. The threat is  Rxe4 + and Black can't really defend that point: }17...f5 18.Nxe4! { Angling to invade and mate via  f8 , as well as check on  d6 . } )( {  C.  }15...Qh4+?! 16.Kd1 Ne7 17.Rf4! { Even stronger than 17.  Kc2 , since the other rook is taboo. }17...Qh1+ 18.Kc2 Qxa1? 19.Rxe4 { Black can only delay, not avert mate. } )16.Nxe4 Qh4! 17.Nf2 { It's still an extra two pawns for Black, but equally his development remains a mess. White is also ready to begin creating threats once again, ideally with  Rg1  and then  Qd6  if the g-pawn advances. }17...cxb5 18.Nxb5 Kf8 19.Rc1! { Bringing the final piece into play to leave White with a powerful initiative.     The threats include  Bd5  and  Nc7 , and Black was ultimately unable to survive in Ilyushchenko-Simmelink, correspondence 2013. } )
