6. Qa4+{ White's main move these days, disrupting Black's development, pinning the a-pawn, and preparing both  b4 - b5  and to sacrifice the  c5 -pawn. }( { Of the alternatives, we can't recommend }6.exd4? e4! { or }{   }6.Nxe5? fxe5 7.Qh5+ Ke7! { , }{ but }{   }6.Bb2!? { is Stockfish-approved, if yet to receive an over-the-board test. After }6...dxe3 7.fxe3 axb4 8.d4 { White definitely has some compensation and this has led to two draws so far in correspondence play. } )( { Following the queen check, Black usually blocks with the bishop. That is by no means forced, although of the alternatives   }6...Nd7? { would be especially welcomed by White as }7.exd4 exd4 8.Nxd4 { is just an extra pawn.      We now have a further divide: }( 6...Qd7  )( 6...Bd7  ){ These variations both lead to some extremely rich and fun positions, but before enjoyably exploring them, we should check two other ways that Black has been known to block the check. } )
6. Qd7
7. Bb5( { Forcing Black to either walk into a major pin }{ ( }7...Nc6? 8.O-O { ) or take the  c6 -square away from his knight. } )( { In the main line (   }6...Bd7 { ), we go }7.b5 Bxc5 8.Bc4 { , }{ but here this seems much less disruptive with Black able to go ... Qd6  before or after ... Ne7 . } )
7. c6
8. Bc4{ Now Black again has some problems to solve over how best to develop his queenside, with White all set to go  O-O  then  exd4 .     Play may also rapidly become quite sharp, especially if Black now opts for one of the three critical replies. }
8. Na6
9. exd4{ And why not? White is now set to castle then crash through in the centre. }
9. exd4( 9...Nxb4 { is no good after }10.O-O { with the idea of  Re1  when black's position is difficult. } )
10. O-O
10. axb4
11. Re1+{ Not an easy check for Black to meet as a piece block will simply lead to him coming under heavy pressure after  Bb2  and  Nxd4 . }
11. Kd8
12. a3( { Alexandr Fier's idea, striving to open lines. White may also be better after }12.Be6 Nxc5! 13.Qxa8 Nxe6 { , }{ but that isn't exactly clear. } )( { Now though   }12...bxa3 13.Bxa3 { will keep Black bottled up, } )( {   }12...Nc7!? 13.Qxb4 { must be a bit better for White with the safer king and Black must be careful with the potential tactics down the a-file. } )
12. Nh6
13. axb4{ With some simple ideas (d2- d3  and  Bb2 ) in mind, as well as a certain queen sacrifice: }
13. Nc7
14. Qxa8
14. Nxa8
15. Rxa8{ The immediate and huge threat is  Be6 . }
15. Kc7
16. Bb2{ White is in no rush to recoup his material and with  Nxd4  and, if needed,  Na3 - c2  on the way, we're not surprised that the engines reward his powerful initiative with a '+4' assessment. }
