1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4
3. f6
4. e3{ A critical challenge after Black's Sämisch-like and pretty critical 3... f6 . White too is allowed to play in and aim to dominate the centre. }
4. e5
5. c5{ We'll introduce this critical space-gainer in the 3... f6  lines. White's advanced queenside pawns may look a little vulnerable, but look too at the  a2 - g8  diagonal where the combination of an early  Qb3  and  Bc4  may well cause Black a headache. }
5. a5
6. Qa4+{ An important check, cutting down Black's options before dropping the queen back to the key  a2 - g8  diagonal. }
6. Bd7
7. b5{ By far the best move, restricting Black's queenside pieces and preparing to bring the light-squared bishop out to  c4 . }
7. dxe3
8. fxe3( { The more dynamic recapture, doing so towards the centre, although it should be noted that Stockfish quite likes the radical }8.Ba3!? exf2+ 9.Kxf2 { for White, maintaining the cramping pawn on  c5 . } )
8. Bxc5
9. Bc4{ White is set to continue development with  Nc3  and  O-O , after which he might even be able to put the half-open f-file to some use, as well as break with  d2 - d4 .     And just how is the black king going to flee the centre? }
9. Bd6
10. Nc3
10. Ne7
11. O-O{ With  Ng5  already a threat, as well as ideas of involving the queen via  b3  or  c2  and/or breaking with  d2 - d4 , White was doing well in Agrest-Tikkanen, Swedish League 2015. }
