22. Red1( { While Black is still very solid, White has a slight pull. We have the more active pieces, may be able to activate the knight with tempo (not least with }22...Qg5 23.Ne4 { ),  a5  looks slightly more vulnerable than  a2 , and there may be tricks against Black's back rank. For example: }{   }22...Qf4 23.g3 { Creating some useful luft while making sure that the black knight lacks any active options. }23...Qg4 24.Qe4! { Continuing to play against the knight by cutting out any ideas of ... Nd4 , as well as preparing to have both white rooks on fully open files. }24...Qxe4 25.Nxe4 { White has slightly the more active knight, a piece which can always be defended with  Rc4  if necessary.     Meanwhile  Rd5  is imminent and there are also, of course, ideas of, if allowed, doubling on the seventh. } )
