[White "8) Reversed Benoni: The Undermining 3...a5"]
[Black "Reversed Benoni: 4...g6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. d4
3. b4{ We now turn to examining what happens when Black decides to meet our flank advance with one of his own. }
3. a5
4. b5{ White's simplest approach, seizing the space on offer. The advanced pawn on  b5  will work well with a fianchettoed bishop on  g2 , although we should note that as well as  g2 - g3 , breaking with  e2 - e3  is very much still on White's radar. }( { Instead, if you're a fan of messy positions, you might prefer }4.Bb2 { when we saw }4...c5 5.bxc5 { in the 3... c5  lines and here }{   }4...e5!? 5.Nxe5 axb4 { is likely the critical continuation. } )( { There's also   }4.Qa4+!? { , }{ which has received some GM attention of late - White angles to claim that }4...Bd7 5.b5 { leaves Black's bishop slightly misplaced on  d7 .     Again, this is a line you may wish to explore, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the straightforward text move which gives White good chances of emerging from the opening with a pleasant position. } )
4. g6
5. g3( { A counter fianchetto and one which makes a lot of sense having gone  b4-b5 , although }5.e3!? { and if }5...dxe3 6.fxe3 Bg7 7.d4 { is also possible if you're feeling ambitious. } )
5. Bg7
6. Bg2{ Consistent as not for the first time we see White encouraging Black to overcommit in the centre. }
6. d3
7. Nc3{ White isn't remotely inconvenienced and now the dark-squared bishop can take up a fine role on  a3 , while it may be possible to play down the e-file with some effect after  O-O  and  exd3 . }
7. dxe2
8. Qxe2{ White already holds a considerable developmental and space advantage, trumps which going  O-O ,  Ba3  and  d2 - d4  will but augment. }
