4. b5{ White's simplest approach, seizing the space on offer. The advanced pawn on  b5  will work well with a fianchettoed bishop on  g2 , although we should note that as well as  g2 - g3 , breaking with  e2 - e3  is very much still on White's radar. }( { Instead, if you're a fan of messy positions, you might prefer }4.Bb2 { when we saw }4...c5 5.bxc5 { in the 3... c5  lines and here }{   }4...e5!? 5.Nxe5 axb4 { is likely the critical continuation. } )( { There's also   }4.Qa4+!? { , }{ which has received some GM attention of late - White angles to claim that }4...Bd7 5.b5 { leaves Black's bishop slightly misplaced on  d7 .     Again, this is a line you may wish to explore, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the straightforward text move which gives White good chances of emerging from the opening with a pleasant position. } )
4. g6
5. g3( { A counter fianchetto and one which makes a lot of sense having gone  b4-b5 , although }5.e3!? { and if }5...dxe3 6.fxe3 Bg7 7.d4 { is also possible if you're feeling ambitious. } )
5. Bg7
6. Bg2{ Consistent as not for the first time we see White encouraging Black to overcommit in the centre. }
6. e5
7. O-O{ Completing kingside development and still hoping to tempt Black forwards in the centre. }
7. Ne7
8. d3{ It's probably time to halt any ideas of central expansion from Black in the centre and now  Ba3  may follow, both causing a few problems down the  a3 - f8  diagonal and ruling out any notion of ... Nd7 - c5 . }
8. c5
9. bxc6( { Opening the centre is consistent, although }9.Ba3!? { followed by  Nbd2  in conjunction with  Ne4  and  e2 - e3  looks quite promising too for White. } )( { After taking on  c6 , White would be quite happy to see }9...bxc6 10.Ba3 { , }{ while against a knight recapture  Na3 - b5  to exploit the hole there is likely to be a decent plan: } )
9. Nbxc6
10. Na3
10. O-O
11. Nb5{ It's not so clear what the knight on  e7  is doing and White definitely enjoyed an edge here in Schatz-Voloshin, German League 1999.     Once again,  Rb1  is likely to prove a useful move, while  Nd2 - e4  will angle to invade on  d6  or even  c5 . Black can prevent that, but only by weakening his position: }
11. h6
12. Nd2
12. f5
13. Rb1{ Black's pawns are going nowhere (... e4  simply drops a pawn and ... f4  would give White a huge square on  e4 ), while White is all set to increase the pressure with  Ba3  or  Nb3  and an undermining  f2 - f4 . }
