1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4
2. dxc4
3. e4{ By no means White's most common move, but a decent one nonetheless, as well as a choice which may slightly catch Black out. }( { Instead,   }3.Na3 a6 4.Nxc4 b5 { and }{   }3.Qa4+ Nd7 { seem fine for Black on the latest evidence, which is likely why plenty of strong players have preferred }{   }3.e3 { .     That's a good move and one which may appeal to the more positional among you.     As we quite like White's game after the steady 3.  e3 , as well as after 3.  e4 , we decided to add a bonus section  on 3.  e3 .    Instead, with 3.  e4  we seize space and also intend to recoup the pawn right away with  Bxc4 . It's a favourite line of the Anglo-French Grandmaster Tony Kosten who even advocated what he rightly called  Kramer's Gambit  (named after the strong American player George Kramer) back in the 2009 publication,  Dangerous Weapons: Flank Openings .    In rough ascending order of popularity, we'll now look at:    }( { ♟️  }3...b5 { & }{   }3...Be6 { trying to hold onto the pawn. } )( { ♟️  }3...Bg4  )( { ♟️  }3...Nc6  )( { ♟️  }3...Nf6  )( { ♟️  }3...c5  )( {  3...Nf6  and  3...c5  can easily transpose into each other, and   }3...e6 4.Bxc4 { can lead towards both: Black almost always then goes either }4...c5 5.d4 { and we're in the 3... c5  lines, or }{   }4...Nf6 { when }5.Nc3 { transposes to the 3... Nf6  lines. } ) )
