[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9a) QGA (Aggressive 3.e4) Greedy 3...b5 / 3...Be6"]
[Black "QGA 3.e4: 3...Be6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. dxc4
3. e4( { First let's examine what happens if Black attempts to hold on to the extra pawn }{ ( }3...b5 { would be topical and fully viable had White a pawn on  d4  and knight back on  g1 , but we haven't which makes it quite dubious). }{ Incidentally, if he doesn't and opts for something most unusual, White should simply continue development with  Bxc4 ,  Nc3 ,  d2 - d4  and  O-O , with ideal, centralised development. } )
3. Be6
4. Ng5{ Taking up the challenge against an extremely rare response from Black, and threatening structural ruin on  e6 . }
4. Qd4
5. Nc3{ Overprotecting  e4  to renew the threat. }
5. Bd7
6. Nf3{ Back again and this looks much more to the point than the 6.a4 of Gaehwiler-Maneluk, Internet (blitz) 2022. Now the black queen only has one safe square if it wants to keep protecting  c4 : }
6. Qc5
7. d4{ A strong pawn sacrifice. }
7. cxd3
8. Be3
8. Qb4
9. Bxd3{ White's significant lead in development supplies more than enough compensation for a pawn, not least when the black queen is still a target.     The main threat is  O-O  followed by  Nd5 , with a timely  Bd4  or  e4 - e5  also likely to prove disruptive for Black, as could even  a2 - a3 . And, yes, we should be delighted if Black were to keep eating: }
9. Qxb2
10. Nd5
10. Kd8
11. Rb1{ Having forced Black into a most sub-optimal defence of  c7 , White kicks the queen and is all set to win material after  Ne5  next move. }
