6. Nc3( { Developing a tempo and aiming for more than the definite pull }6.b3 e6! 7.bxc4 Bb7 8.cxb5 Bxe4 9.Be2 { supplies. Of course, 7.  Nxb5  is now the threat and }{   }6...b4? 7.Qa4+ { and }{   }6...Qb6?! 7.b3! { look quite unhealthy for Black, who has merely weakened his position while falling somewhat behind in development. } )( {   }6...a6? 7.Nxb5 axb5 8.Rxa8 Bb7 { could be compared to a similar line in the QGA proper: }{   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 dxc4 3.e4 b5!? 4.a4 c6 5.axb5 cxb5 6.Nc3 a6 7.Nxb5 axb5 8.Rxa8 Bb7 { , }{ with some compensation. Some Black players might play this way if they aren't aware of the Reti move-order subtleties; White has played  Nf3  instead of  d2 - d4 , so we have one more piece developed and are one move closer to castling, we don't need to worry about attacks on the  d4  pawn, and Black doesn't have options of ... Bb4 + to speed up their development } )
6. Bd7
7. d3( { A new, engine-approved idea to open lines. Instead, }7.d4 e6 8.Be2 { merely supplied decent compensation in Deviprasath-Baches Garcia, Internet  (blitz) 2021. After 7.  d3 , White simply wants to go 8.  dxc4  and Black would be well advised to reject greed. } )
7. b4
8. Na4{ A knight on the rim...is not always dim.     This position already looks quite promising for White, who is likely to prefer  d3 - d4  and  Bxc4  to  dxc4 , and who also has the strong idea of  Be3  and  Nb6 . }
8. cxd3
9. Be3{ With a definite threat to exploit the potential pin down the a-file, and already the engines can see nothing better for Black than an unconvincing exchange sacrifice. }
9. Nc6
10. Nc5( { Continuing to hunt down the light squares, while hoping for }10...Bg4? 11.Qa4 { . } )
10. e5
11. Nxd7
11. Qxd7
12. Qxd3( { White is yet to regain his pawn, but is clearly doing extremely well, with  13. Qa6  and  14. Bb5  one threat, that of   }13.Qxd7+ Kxd7 14.Bb5 { another, and all the while as Black finds himself rather vulnerable on  a7 ,  e5  and especially the light squares. } )
