1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. dxc4
3. e4
3. Bg4
4. Bxc4{ Naturally we recoup the pawn and now both 5.  Bxf7 + and 5.  Ne5  are threats. }( { Just note that after }4...Nc6? 5.Qb3! { is likely even stronger than }5.Bxf7+ { , as we'll see via a }{   }3...Nc6 4.Bxc4 Bg4? 5.Qb3 { move order in the }3...Nc6 { lines.  } )
4. e6
5. d4( { An extremely rare move, transposing to a most unusual form of the Queen's Gambit Accepted (after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 dxc4 3.Nf3 Bg4 { White would likely go }4.Ne5 { , }( { not }4.e4 e6 5.Bxc4 { , }{ which is our position here. }{ It's in keeping with our uncompromising stance though, and looks like a reasonable alternative to the more common 5.  O-O . } ) )( { At lower levels, }5.Qb3 { might tempt you too, since }5...b6? 6.Ne5 { leaves Black in huge trouble, but }5...Bxf3 { is OK for him, and if Kosten's }6.gxf3!? { then }6...Bc5! { . }{    With 5.  d4 !? White simply wants to complete development with  Nc3  and  Be3 , after which  h2 - h3  and  O-O  will be options, as well as perhaps a quick  d4 - d5 .  Qb3  is very much still an idea too if Black doesn't go ... Nc6  and his critical response sees  d4  quickly being targeted. } )( { Note too that }5...Bxf3 6.gxf3 Nc6 7.Be3 { leads to the same position as we'll explore via }{   }5...Nc6 6.Be3 Bxf3 7.gxf3 { . } )
5. Be7
6. Nc3
6. Nf6
7. Be3{ Model development from White who is now all set to castle. }
7. c6
8. O-O( { We prefer this to the }8.a4 { of Terentiev-Romanenko, Pechora 2011.     If Black now castles then  h3   Bh5 ;  g4  would push his bishop back to what is a rather inactive spot once White has shored up  e4 . White can always drop his own light-squared bishop back to  d3 , with the queen's rook likely to take up a decent role on  c1 , fighting against any attempts to break with ... c5 . And queenside expansion need not be feared: } )
8. b5
9. Bd3{ White has a nice position, with  Rc1 ,  Qe2  and  h2 - h3  all likely to prove useful. }
9. b4
10. Na4
10. Qa5
11. b3{ Simply overprotecting the knight ahead of clamping down on  c5  with  Rc1 , which may usefully be followed up by  Rc4  at some stage. White is also set to go  h2 - h3  and may even (most likely after first  Rc4 ) meet ... Bh5  with  g4   Bg6 ;  Qc2 . }
