9. Nxd4
10. Qxa7
10. Nc2+
11. Ke2( { Suddenly   }12.Qa8+ Kd7 13.Bb5+ { is a significant threat, which explains why Black must now reject the hanging rook. } )
11. Nxe3
12. fxe3( { With the dark-squared bishop gone and  d1  covered, this is simpler and at least as effective as }12.Qa8+ { . } )( { Now   }13.Rad1 { is a big threat, and if }13...Bd6 14.Bb5 { to cut off the king and also meet }14...c6 { with the devastating }15.Bxc6! bxc6 16.Na4 { . As such, Black must again counter with his queen. } )
12. Qg5
13. Rhd1{ With a mating threat. }( 13.Rhg1 { is also quite promising. }{ And now checks on  g2  and  g1  can calmly be answered by  Bf1 . } )
13. Bd6
14. Rd4{ A fine, multipurpose move to leave White doing rather well. His king will now take shelter on  d3  and still be happier than its counterpart.     While White might go  Qa8 +  Kd7 ;  Qxb7 , we'd probably prefer to leave the queen actively placed on  a7  for now and instead strike forwards with  Nb5  or  f3 - f4  and  e4 - e5 . }
