1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. dxc4
3. e3
3. b5
4. a4{ Immediately challenging the extended black queenside. Clearly if 3... b5  worked, there would be a question mark over 3.  e3 , but it doesn't as White can seize an early initiative and/or advantage. }
4. b4
5. Bxc4{ Black's early advance of the b-pawn makes a strange impression, but this is still the best that he has after his misguided third move. White threatens  Ne5  followed by  Qf3  and should emerge with a pleasant edge thanks to his superior development and more compact set-up. }
5. e6
6. O-O{ Continuing to prioritise kingside development before deciding what to do in the centre. Here White doesn't have to head for QGA-type waters with  d2 - d4 , as we'll see, and in any case  a4 - a5  may well be a useful space-gainer. }
6. Nf6
7. d3( { The immediate }7.a5!? { is also tempting, but in case we prefer to place the d-pawn on  d3 , not  d4 .     The reason is simple: Black's light-squared bishop is likely to head for  b7  from where it will now bite on granite after our  e3 - e4 . } )
7. Nbd7( { After }7...c5 { here White can play }8.e4 { will a very similar type of position to the game or  a4 - a5  or  Nbd2  first, all of which is thematic - move orders don’t seem too important here. } )
8. a5{ The aforementioned space grab, ruling out ... a5  for Black who may now have to go ... c5  to keep  b4  defended. White's ability to meet ... Bb7  with  a5 - a6  is also a little annoying for Black. }
8. a6
9. Nbd2( { There's also nothing wrong with }9.e4 { first, but the knight certainly wants to head to a fine post on  b3 , supporting  a5  if needed and mainly challenging for control of  d4  and  c5 . } )
9. Bb7
10. e4
10. Be7
11. Nb3{ This left White with a pleasant edge in Harika-Cramling, Beijing (blitz) 2014, in part due to Black's fairly restricted bishops.     White's greater central space is a useful asset and while Black can get in ... c5 , White will complete development with  Bf4  and  Qe2 , leaving Black struggling somewhat for counterplay. White may then play in the centre or perhaps prepare a strong kingside advance with  h2 - h3 ,  Nfd2 ,  Bh2  (or  Be3 ) and  f2 - f4 . }
