2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. dxc4
3. e3
3. Be6
4. Ng5( { A critical and promising response against Black's visually-surprising third move, one which has attracted a fair bit of grandmaster support over the years. If, though, you really insist on something calmer then do just go }4.Na3 { followed by recouping the pawn with  Nxc4 . } )
4. Bd7( { if }4...Qd5 5.Nxe6 { , }{ and if }5...Qxe6 6.Qa4+ { . } )
5. Bxc4{ Black's bishop invariably goes to  d5  and this is likely why. The bishop isn't too active on  d7  and White should emerge with an edge. }
5. e6
6. f4( { A very good case can, of course, also be made for }6.Nf3 { , }{ but why not seize some useful space so and clamp down on  e5  in the process? } )
6. Nf6
7. Nc3{ White continues to contest control of the central squares,  e4  and  d5 .     Black is quite solid, but we'd slightly prefer to take White here who will castle short, may consider ideas of  Qf3  (even after  Nf3 - e5  if the knight is kicked back from  g5 ), and will bring the dark-squared bishop to a decent post on  b2 . }
