1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. dxc4
3. e3
3. Be6
4. Ng5( { A critical and promising response against Black's visually-surprising third move, one which has attracted a fair bit of grandmaster support over the years. If, though, you really insist on something calmer then do just go }4.Na3 { followed by recouping the pawn with  Nxc4 . } )
4. Bd5
5. e4{ The star follow-up and point of White's play. Will Black now retreat to  c6 , returning the pawn or continue in ambitious vein? }
5. Bc6
6. Bxc4{ Regaining the pawn with a threat. }
6. e6
7. d3{ Shoring up  e4  to keep the bishop on  c6  restricted when the knight retreats from  g5 . }( { Ambitious souls may also wish to consider }7.d4!? { with the ideas of }7...Be7 8.h4 { and }7...h6 8.Nxe6!? Bb4+ 9.Nc3 fxe6 10.O-O!? { with definitive compensation for the piece. } )
7. Be7
8. Qh5( { Direct play, angling to gain the two bishops on  g5 . Simple chess is also decent here too: }8.Nf3 { followed by  Nc3  and  O-O . } )
8. g6
9. Qg4{ Threatening to take on  f7  and it's not completely impossible that Black may miss or underestimate the threat. Indeed, he did in one of only two tests of 8.  Qh5  so far: }
9. b5
10. Nxf7{ The same idea would work against other 9th moves such as ... h6 . }
10. Qd4
11. Bxe6{ Maintaining control and an important bishop. }
11. Nf6
12. Qe2{ The knight will emerge via  g5  and White is just two pawns to the good, Kosten-Brochet, Le Mans 2004. }
