2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. dxc4
3. e3
3. Be6
4. Ng5( { A critical and promising response against Black's visually-surprising third move, one which has attracted a fair bit of grandmaster support over the years. If, though, you really insist on something calmer then do just go }4.Na3 { followed by recouping the pawn with  Nxc4 . } )
4. Bd5
5. e4{ The star follow-up and point of White's play. Will Black now retreat to  c6 , returning the pawn or continue in ambitious vein? }
5. e6
6. d4( { Defending the knight and claiming the centre rather than get involved in the pretty murky mess that is }6.exd5 Qxg5 7.dxe6 fxe6 8.d4 Qg6 9.Be2 Nf6 { . } )
6. Bc6
7. Nc3{ Overprotecting  e4  lest the knight is kicked back from  g5 . This sensible idea was also endorsed in Adrien Demuth's generally excellent book 'The Modernized Reti'. }( { Once again though, those of an attacking, Tal-like bent may wish to consider }7.Bxc4!? { , }{ with the ideas of }7...Be7 8.h4! ( 8.Nxf7!? { was even seen in the stem game with 6.  d4 , W. Bauer-Rausis, German League 2012 }{ and } ){   }7...h6 8.Nxe6!? { . }{ 7.  Nc3  is at least as good though, as White introduces the idea of crashing through towards the black king with  d4 - d5  and may also meet ... Nf6  with  e4 - e5 . } )
7. Bb4
8. Bxc4{ With Black's bishop away from the kingside, White should simply get on with swift development. }
8. h6
9. Nf3( { A simple approach rather than really speculate with }9.Nxe6!? fxe6 10.O-O { , }{ highly tempting though this is. } )
9. Bxe4
10. O-O{ The bishop is now attacked and Black must also watch out for a powerful breakthrough that could be  d4 - d5 . }
10. Bxc3
11. bxc3{ As analysed by John Watson for ChessPublishing, this supplies 'full compensation'.     White has the two bishops, safer king and is all set to complete development with  Re1  and  Ba3 , while ... Bd5  should usually be met by  Bd3 , keeping pieces on and angling for a  c3 - c4  then  d4 - d5  breakthrough. Let's examine one possible continuation: }
11. Ne7
12. Re1
12. Bd5
13. Bd3{ Maintaining the bishop-pair while intending to expand with  Ne5 ,  c3 - c4  and  Qg4 , which should secure a strong initiative. }
13. O-O
14. Nh4{ An excellent idea, spotted and pointed out by Demuth. White opens up a route for the queen to  g4  and will enjoy promising attacking chances with his queen, bishops, knight itching to sacrifice itself on  g6  and even a rook lift possible via  e3 . }
