6. O-O{ Making the king safe while remaining flexible in the centre. }
6. Nf6
7. Qc2( { A new idea in this precise position, although the concept is known in general and, indeed,  5. Qc2  has been tried in this line. Instead, }7.d4 O-O { seemed pretty solid for Black in Vladimirov-Gleizerov, Podolsk 1992, so instead we increase our light-square control and have two main ideas in mind: reversed Sicilian style development with  a2 - a3 ,  b2 - b4  and  Bb2 , and tickling the black kingside with a timely  Ng5 .     That latter idea also helps prevent ... e4 , an advance White should rarely want to allow. } )
7. O-O
8. a3
8. a5
9. b3{ Black has ruled out  b2 - b4 , which might help his knight on  c6  to breathe slightly more easily, but there is a now a small hole on  b5  and White can still set up with powerful-looking bishops on the  a2 - g8  and  a1 - h8  diagonals. }
9. Bg4
10. Ng5( { Thematic, if far from forced. Those with some Sicilian experience might be fairly happy after }10.Be2 { followed by  d2 - d3  and  Bb2 , while the engines clamour for }{   }10.Bb2!? { , }{ intending }10...Bxf3 11.gxf3 { followed by  Kg2 ,  Rg1  and  Kh1 , with some attacking chances for White. } )( { After }10.Ng5 { White actually has a threat and would be especially delighted to see Black walk right into it with }10...Qe7?? 11.Nd5 { when he would have to resign. } )
10. h6
11. f3{ White is quite happy to sacrifice a pawn to open up the f-file. }
11. hxg5
12. fxg4
12. Nxg4
13. Qg6{ Ouch. This already looks most unpleasant for Black, with White simply threatening to crash through on  f7 . }
13. Nh6
14. Ne4
14. Be7
15. Qh5{ Retreating the queen before being forced to and leaving White with superb compensation and a large advantage. White may calmly continue with  Bb2  and  Rf3  followed by  Rg3  or  Raf1 , while there are even ideas of  Rf6 !? should the black queen step off the  h4 - d8  diagonal. }
