1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. dxc4
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Bxc4( { Black usually now elects, QGA style, to close the long diagonal without delay, although he can also begin with }4...c5 { , }{ transposing after }5.b3 e6 6.Bb2 { . Other options for Black are pretty rare and should be welcomed by White. } )
4. e6
5. b3( { White's main moves by far here are }5.d4 { and }5.O-O { , }{ which is often followed by  Qe2  and a timely  d2 - d4 , looking to transpose into a favourable type of QGA.     However, we don't have to transpose so and can instead place the dark-squared bishop on a decent diagonal with 5.  b3 !?, an old favourite of that great creative thinker, the Romanian GM Mihai Suba (author of the seminal work 'Dynamic Chess Strategy'), as well as a move which has appealed in more recent times to both Jan-Krzysztof Duda and Daniel Dardha. } )
5. a6
6. Bb2( { Completing the fianchetto and play will now transpose to our main line after }6...c5 7.O-O { . Expanding immediately is instead a little risky for Black: } )
6. b5
7. Be2{ A forced retreat here, of course, but now  a2 - a4  will be quick to force some form of queenside concession from Black. }
7. Bb7
8. a4
8. b4
9. O-O( { As we saw via a   }4...a6 5.O-O b5 6.Be2 { move order, White is slightly for choice with  d2 - d3  followed by  e3 - e4  and  Nbd2 - c4  the immediate plan. } )
