1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. dxc4
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Bxc4( { Black usually now elects, QGA style, to close the long diagonal without delay, although he can also begin with }4...c5 { , }{ transposing after }5.b3 e6 6.Bb2 { . Other options for Black are pretty rare and should be welcomed by White. } )
4. e6
5. b3( { White's main moves by far here are }5.d4 { and }5.O-O { , }{ which is often followed by  Qe2  and a timely  d2 - d4 , looking to transpose into a favourable type of QGA.     However, we don't have to transpose so and can instead place the dark-squared bishop on a decent diagonal with 5.  b3 !?, an old favourite of that great creative thinker, the Romanian GM Mihai Suba (author of the seminal work 'Dynamic Chess Strategy'), as well as a move which has appealed in more recent times to both Jan-Krzysztof Duda and Daniel Dardha. } )
5. c5
6. Bb2( { Completing the fianchetto. White will likely castle kingside next, after which it will be time to decide what to do in the centre:  Be2, d2-d3  and  e3-e4  is very much a plan to again obstruct Black's light-squared bishop, but a timely  d2-d4  isn't entirely out of the question if Black does something unusual (or you're just happy to transpose to the  b3  lines of the QGA), like with }6...g6 7.d4 { .     Finally, we should also mention that if Black develops very slowly White might also wish to consider aggressive-looking ideas in  Qc2  and  Nc3 , as well as  Ne5  and  f2 - f4 . } )
6. Nc6
7. O-O{ Housing the king while keeping the d-pawn flexible. }
7. Bd6
8. d4{ With Black's bishop on  d6 , not  e7 , this advance becomes more tempting, as in Makarov-Drasko, Podgorica 1993. White is now ready to reopen the long diagonal by exchanging on  c5  and  d8 , and will obtain some pressure even in the event of an exchange on  d4 : }
8. cxd4
9. Nxd4
9. Nxd4
10. Qxd4{ The difference between Black's bishop being on  d6  and  e7  becomes clear. With  Rd1  and possibly  Qh4  on the way, White definitely enjoys some pressure and a small edge. }
