6. Bb2( { Completing the fianchetto. White will likely castle kingside next, after which it will be time to decide what to do in the centre:  Be2, d2-d3  and  e3-e4  is very much a plan to again obstruct Black's light-squared bishop, but a timely  d2-d4  isn't entirely out of the question if Black does something unusual (or you're just happy to transpose to the  b3  lines of the QGA), like with }6...g6 7.d4 { .     Finally, we should also mention that if Black develops very slowly White might also wish to consider aggressive-looking ideas in  Qc2  and  Nc3 , as well as  Ne5  and  f2 - f4 . } )
6. a6
7. O-O( { Housing the king and keeping open the options of both  d2-d4  and  Be2  and  d2-d3 , while again hoping to entice  ...b5 . With this move order, an independent, Reti-like alternative is }7.Ne5!? Nbd7 8.f4 { , }{ as was seen in Duda-Mamedyarov, Aimchess Rapid 2022, no less. } )
7. Be7
8. Be2{ Our favourite policy, keeping the bishop away from attack and allowing White to consider ideas of both  d2 - d3  and  d2 - d4 . }
8. Nc6
9. d4( { Expanding this way while only heading into QGA waters now that Black has spent a move on  ...a6  and note too that   }7...Nc6 8.Be2 Be7 9.d4 { would also lead to this position. } )( { Observe as well that there's also nothing wrong with }9.d3 { , }{ setting up as we saw White doing after }{   }6...Nc6 7.O-O Be7 8.Be2 O-O 9.d3 { . Lest you prefer that here too and to improve our overall understanding of the resulting positions, we'll see how play may pan out in the illustrative game, Grivas-Velikov, Xanthi 1991. } )
9. O-O
10. dxc5( { Forcing the pace to try and exploit White's freer development, while refusing to fear a queen exchange (the alternative is }10.Nbd2 { and if }10...cxd4 11.Nxd4 { followed by  Bf3 ). } )
10. Bxc5
11. Nbd2{ Now keeping the queens on as White intends to swing the lady west (to  c2  or  b1 ) followed by causing trouble for her counterpart with  Rd1 . }
11. b6
12. Qb1{ An even better square than  c2  as the queen can't be attacked here.     Not only was  Rd1  on the way in Bischoff-Karpatchev, Baunatal 2002, but White enjoyed definite attacking chances, as well as a pleasant advantage, with both  Ng5  and  Ne4  high on the agenda. }
