1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. e3{ A simple response to our early Reti central challenge is  2...e6 , very much in Queen's Gambit Declined fashion. }( { You may now be happy to transpose with   }3.d4 { to the QGD, but it's also possible to remain within Reti waters, be that with }{      }3.g3 { (as Sam Shankland endorses in his Neo-Catalan Repertoire) or }{   }3.e3 { , }{ as we'll be covering here.     This little move was known back in the days of James Mason and J.H. Blackburne, then received a bit of attention at the height of the Soviet chess world from David Bronstein and Vasily Smyslov before appealing to a young Ulf Andersson. In more recent times, Jan-Krzysztof Duda has quite liked our recommended approach, which sees White take control of  d4  ahead of fianchettoing the queen's bishop, just as we will do against the Slav. } )( { After  3. e3 , Black usually continues in standard QGD fashion with   }3...Nf6 { , }{ although he does have a few alternatives.     Of these, we will cover }3...c6 4.b3 { in the Slav Rare 3rd Moves, while }{   }3...dxc4 4.Bxc4 { would take play into the realm of the QGA. That leaves:     ♟️Rare Third Moves }( { ♟️  }3...c5  )( { ♟️  }3...Nf6  ) )
