8. b3( { A straightforward approach, preparing to bring the bishop to  a3  then go  Rc1 . Here too }8.b4!? { is very much an idea, seizing space just like we saw White doing with the black knight on  f6 . } )
8. Bb7
9. Ba3{ All is now set for  Rc1 , but with the knight on  c3  not yet defended, perhaps Black may now be tempted to break out? }
9. c5
10. Rc1{ Covering the knight and so threatening to take on  c5 . }
10. cxd4
11. Nxd4{ A fine post indeed for the knight. White now has ideas of not just  cxd5  in conjunction with  Bf3 , but  Ndb5  or even  Ncb5 . }
11. e5
12. Ndb5{ Simply threatening to invade on  d6  then take on  d5 . }
12. d4
13. exd4
13. exd4
14. Nd5{ A powerful leap as White continues to make use of the dominant bishop on  a3 . }
14. Nbc6
15. Bf3{ Black remains under heavy pressure with White renewing the threat to win material via a capture on  e7  and there are also definite issues to do with  Nd6  and just  Re1 . In short, Black has suffered an opening disaster. }
