1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3{ A simple response to our early Reti central challenge is  2...e6 , very much in Queen's Gambit Declined fashion. }( { You may now be happy to transpose with   }3.d4 { to the QGD, but it's also possible to remain within Reti waters, be that with }{      }3.g3 { (as Sam Shankland endorses in his Neo-Catalan Repertoire) or }{   }3.e3 { , }{ as we'll be covering here.     This little move was known back in the days of James Mason and J.H. Blackburne, then received a bit of attention at the height of the Soviet chess world from David Bronstein and Vasily Smyslov before appealing to a young Ulf Andersson. In more recent times, Jan-Krzysztof Duda has quite liked our recommended approach, which sees White take control of  d4  ahead of fianchettoing the queen's bishop, just as we will do against the Slav. } )( { After  3. e3 , Black usually continues in standard QGD fashion with   }3...Nf6 { , }{ although he does have a few alternatives.     Of these, we will cover }3...c6 4.b3 { in the Slav Rare 3rd Moves, while }{   }3...dxc4 4.Bxc4 { would take play into the realm of the QGA. That leaves:     ♟️Rare Third Moves }( { ♟️  }3...c5  )( { ♟️  }3...Nf6  ) )
3. g6
4. d4{ A change of approach from the  b2 - b3  and  Bb2  plan, if also a very logical advance now that Black will have a bishop on the long dark-square diagonal. }
4. Bg7
5. Nc3{ Straightforward, classical development. White will likely now continue with  Be2  and  O-O  and may then consider a queenside fianchetto after all. }
5. Ne7
6. Be2( { Calmly preparing to castle, although if like Simon you're a big fan of Harry, }6.h4!? { may not be totally ridiculous now that Black's knight isn't on  f6 . } )
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. b6
8. b3( { A straightforward approach, preparing to bring the bishop to  a3  then go  Rc1 . Here too }8.b4!? { is very much an idea, seizing space just like we saw White doing with the black knight on  f6 . } )
8. Bb7
9. Ba3{ All is now set for  Rc1 , but with the knight on  c3  not yet defended, perhaps Black may now be tempted to break out? }
9. c5
10. Rc1{ Covering the knight and so threatening to take on  c5 . }
10. Nd7
11. cxd5{ Opening up the c-file and planning on laying siege to the  c5  point with  Na4 . }
11. Nxd5
12. Nxd5( { A strong exchange and going after  c5  so is a much better choice than }12.Na4 Bc6! { when }13.dxc5? { would run into }13...b5 { . } )
12. Bxd5
13. Bb5{ There's no rush to take on  c5  with the pawn pinned. Instead, White activates and increases the pressure.     Sooner or later, we'll annex  c5  when Black's bishop-pair will give him a bit but nowhere near full compensation for the pawn. }
