1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3
3. c5
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. d4{ Transposing to a line of the Tarrasch Defence as we play to gradually take control and leave Black with a long-term weakness on  d5 . }( { If now }5...a6 { we’ll see }6.Nc3 { (threatening to take on  c5  then  d5 ) }6...Nf6 7.b3 { via a }{   }3...Nf6 4.Nc3 a6 5.b3 c5 6.cxd5 exd5 7.d4 { move order. } )
5. Nf6
6. Bb5+( { Magnus Carlsen no less has been happy to check so, as White continues to develop a tempo, while asking Black a slightly tricky question: does he want to keep pieces on or exchange the light-squared bishops? Black usually now elects to block with either: }6...Bd7 { or }6...Nc6 { . } )
6. Nc6
7. O-O( { Our favourite policy and likely also a stronger one than getting involved of the complexities of }7.Ne5 Bd7 { . } )
7. a6
8. Bxc6+{ Forcing the pace as Black will now be a little vulnerable down the c-file. }
8. bxc6
9. Qc2{ Simply threatening to bag a pawn. }
9. cxd4
10. exd4{ The right pawn to capture. Now  Qxc6 + is a threat and with both  Ne5  and  Nc3 - a4  on their way, Black is already under some pressure. }
