1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3
3. c5
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. d4{ Transposing to a line of the Tarrasch Defence as we play to gradually take control and leave Black with a long-term weakness on  d5 . }( { If now }5...a6 { we’ll see }6.Nc3 { (threatening to take on  c5  then  d5 ) }6...Nf6 7.b3 { via a }{   }3...Nf6 4.Nc3 a6 5.b3 c5 6.cxd5 exd5 7.d4 { move order. } )
5. Nf6
6. Bb5+( { Magnus Carlsen no less has been happy to check so, as White continues to develop a tempo, while asking Black a slightly tricky question: does he want to keep pieces on or exchange the light-squared bishops? Black usually now elects to block with either: }6...Bd7 { or }6...Nc6 { . } )
6. Nc6
7. O-O( { Our favourite policy and likely also a stronger one than getting involved of the complexities of }7.Ne5 Bd7 { . } )
7. Bd6
8. dxc5( { Isolating the d-pawn ahead of going  Nc3  and fianchettoing on the queenside }{ ( }8.Bxc6+!? bxc6 9.Qc2 { is also quite an interesting approach). } )
8. Bxc5
9. Nc3( { Forcing Black to keep his king's knight on  f6  for now, although you can also begin with }9.b3 { if you prefer. } )
9. O-O
10. b3{ Our favourite approach, intending to involve the queenside pieces with  Bb2  and  Rc1 . }
10. Bg4
11. Bb2
11. a6
12. Bxc6( { White refuses to fear the pin on  f3  (if you really do then }12.Be2 { isn't so terrible, if less of a challenge for Black), and follows in the footsteps of the world champion by preparing to obtain some pressure down the c-file. } )
12. bxc6
13. Rc1{ Forcing Black on to the defensive as  Nxd5  is now a rather large threat. }
13. Bd6
14. Ne2{ An important concept, unpinning, provoking the exchange on  c3  and preparing to take on  c6 . }
14. Bxf3
15. gxf3
15. Rc8
16. Qd3{ White is definitely a bit better with Black's queen tied down to covering  f6 ,  a6  weak and White always able to expand with  f3 - f4  or simply go  Ng3  if he wants. }
