[Round "?"]
[White "13) QGD: 3...Nf6 Rare 4th Moves"]
[Black "QGD: 4...g6 "]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { A familiar method of development from how we met the Slav.    Here too we activate the knight before going  b2-b3  }{ ( }4.b3 c5 { isn't such a bad version of a Tarrasch for Black). } )( { Now   }4...c6 5.b3 { would, of course, take play back into the realm of the Semi-Slav sidelines  and here we'll focus our coverage on: }( 4...c5  )( 4...dxc4  )( 4...a6  )( 4...Nbd7  )( 4...Be7  ){ A couple of minor options should also be briefly mentioned. } )
4. g6
5. b3{ Consistent with our general approach and it also makes sense to compete for control of the long diagonal. }
5. Bg7
6. Ba3( { An idea we've seen before. Here White simply prevents Black from castling, while preparing to complete queenside development with  d2-d4  and  Rc1 . It seems decent enough, although Vincent Keymer was happy to simply go }6.Bb2 O-O 7.d4 { in Keymer-Barria Zuniga, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022. } )
6. Ne4
7. Qc2{ White is now set to take control of the centre with  d2 - d4 . }
7. Nxc3
8. dxc3{ This is quite an unusual structure, but White may well be slightly for choice.  Rd1  will obtain some pressure down the d-file (or even 0-0-0), Black still can't castle and White may even consider early aggression with  h2 - h4 - h5 . }
