1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { A familiar method of development from how we met the Slav.    Here too we activate the knight before going  b2-b3  }{ ( }4.b3 c5 { isn't such a bad version of a Tarrasch for Black). } )( { Now   }4...c6 5.b3 { would, of course, take play back into the realm of the Semi-Slav sidelines  and here we'll focus our coverage on: }( 4...c5  )( 4...dxc4  )( 4...a6  )( 4...Nbd7  )( 4...Be7  ){ A couple of minor options should also be briefly mentioned. } )
4. b6
5. b3( { Our preferred fianchetto, although here another typical Reti concept in }5.cxd5 exd5 6.g3!? { is possible too, as used by Vincent Keymer and Wesley So in some blitz games. } )
5. Bb7
6. Bb2( { Now play is very likely to transpose into the  4...Be7  lines of the QGD  after }6...Be7 7.cxd5 { , }{ although Gukesh did once try a more ambitious piece development here. } )
6. Nbd7
7. Qc2( { Remaining in Reti waters, which }7.d4 Bd6 { didn't really in Vassallo Barroche-Gukesh, Guimaraes 2021. } )( { After }7.Qc2 { White may be able to go }{   }8.cxd5 { and if }8...exd5 { then }9.Bd3 { , }{ keeping the d-pawn at home while angling to obtain some early pressure after  O-O  and  Ne2 . Black should also keep an eye on the  b5 -square. } )
7. Bd6
8. cxd5
8. exd5
9. Nb5{ Netting the bishop-pair and a clear advantage thanks to the powerful, soon-to-be-unopposed bishop on  b2 . }
