2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { A familiar method of development from how we met the Slav.    Here too we activate the knight before going  b2-b3  }{ ( }4.b3 c5 { isn't such a bad version of a Tarrasch for Black). } )( { Now   }4...c6 5.b3 { would, of course, take play back into the realm of the Semi-Slav sidelines  and here we'll focus our coverage on: }( 4...c5  )( 4...dxc4  )( 4...a6  )( 4...Nbd7  )( 4...Be7  ){ A couple of minor options should also be briefly mentioned. } )
4. c5
5. cxd5{ Prudently exchanging to reduce Black's options in the centre. }
5. exd5
6. d4{ Heading into Tarrasch waters after all as White plays to saddle Black with an IQP. }
6. c4( { If now }6...cxd4 7.Nxd4 { when White is set to quickly complete development with  Be2  (or  Bb5 +) and  O-O , followed by our favourite  b2 - b3  and  Bb2  approach. Here there’s also }7.exd4!? { - compare with what now follows after }{   }6...Nc6 7.Bb5 cxd4 8.exd4!? { . } )
7. Bd2{ An engine-approved if rare counter to Black's ambitious early gain of space. White overprotects the knight on  c3  so he can go  b2 - b3  next without ... Bb4  being an annoying response. }
7. Be6( 7...a6 8.a4 { (Denying Black ... b5 ) }8...Bb4 9.b3! { (Chipping away at  c4 ) }9...Qa5 10.Qc2 { White retains control and likely has an edge, since }10...Bf5?? { would not, of course, be wise for Black: }11.Qxf5 Bxc3 12.Qc8+ { . } )
8. b3( { Wasting no time undermining the pawn chain. White already threatens   }9.bxc4 dxc4 10.Qa4+ { and Black only appears to have one decent response, which is not to come under pressure on  b7  after }{   }8...cxb3?! 9.Qxb3 { . } )
8. Bb4
9. bxc4{ By no means forced, but obtaining a central majority is certainly consistent, as well as tempting. }
9. dxc4
10. Be2{ This position could really do with a test. White is now set to castle, after which he may be able to activate via  Ng5  and  Bf3 , with another important concept that of  Qb1 , obtaining some pressure down the light squares while taking control of some useful squares down the  b1 - h7  diagonal. }
