1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { A familiar method of development from how we met the Slav.    Here too we activate the knight before going  b2-b3  }{ ( }4.b3 c5 { isn't such a bad version of a Tarrasch for Black). } )( { Now   }4...c6 5.b3 { would, of course, take play back into the realm of the Semi-Slav sidelines  and here we'll focus our coverage on: }( 4...c5  )( 4...dxc4  )( 4...a6  )( 4...Nbd7  )( 4...Be7  ){ A couple of minor options should also be briefly mentioned. } )
4. c5
5. cxd5{ Prudently exchanging to reduce Black's options in the centre. }
5. exd5
6. d4{ Heading into Tarrasch waters after all as White plays to saddle Black with an IQP. }
6. Nc6
7. Bb5{ Our favourite approach from the 3... c5  lines of the QGD, and we now have the same position as in those 6... Nc6  lines , but with White having played  Nc3  instead of castling, which is by no means the end of the world.     White has slightly reduced his options, but play may well land up transposing after  O-O , a pawn exchange on  d4  or  c5 , and  b2 - b3 . }( { Note too that   }7...Bd7 8.O-O { would now be an immediate transposition to our coverage there, as would }{   }7...Bd6 8.dxc5 Bxc5 9.O-O { . } )
