[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { A familiar method of development from how we met the Slav.    Here too we activate the knight before going  b2-b3  }{ ( }4.b3 c5 { isn't such a bad version of a Tarrasch for Black). } )( { Now   }4...c6 5.b3 { would, of course, take play back into the realm of the Semi-Slav sidelines  and here we'll focus our coverage on: }( 4...c5  )( 4...dxc4  )( 4...a6  )( 4...Nbd7  )( 4...Be7  ){ A couple of minor options should also be briefly mentioned. } )
4. dxc4
5. Bxc4( { Naturally we recapture the pawn. Now we are in QGA waters(   }2...dxc4 3.e3 Nf6 4.Bxc4 e6 5.O-O { ), but having gone  Nc3  instead of castling. That's not quite as useful a move, although it does allow White to expand quickly with  e3 - e4 , as well simply go in for a queenside fianchetto after all.     We should also add that while this sub-variation has been relatively topical at fairly high levels of late, whereas the elite are happy in both Queen's Gambit Accepted and Declined waters, many club and internet opponents will not be. } )
5. a6
6. O-O{ White refuses to commit to anything on the queenside for now and prepares to drop the bishop back to  e2  if attacked. }
6. c5
7. Be2( { A prophylactic retreat designed to keep Black guessing as to White's intentions. If you don't mind playing with an IQP, }7.a4 { followed by  Qe2 ,  Rfd1  and  d2 - d4  is not such a bad set-up either. } )
7. b5
8. b3{ Only now that Black has expanded we eschew  d2 - d4  to take control of  c4 . This is to stymie Black's advancing pawns and preparing our favourite queenside fianchetto after all. }
8. Bb7
9. Bb2
9. Bd6
10. d3( { We slightly prefer this to the }10.Qc2 { of K.Schmitt-Philipowski, Eupen (rapid) 2000.     Black should be OK here, but at least White will manage to thematically reduce the impact of the bishop on  b7  with  e3 - e4  and may also find  a2 - a4  a fairly useful queenside challenge, angling for ... b4 ?!;  Nb1  and  Nbd2 - c4 . } )
