5. Bxc4( { Naturally we recapture the pawn. Now we are in QGA waters(   }2...dxc4 3.e3 Nf6 4.Bxc4 e6 5.O-O { ), but having gone  Nc3  instead of castling. That's not quite as useful a move, although it does allow White to expand quickly with  e3 - e4 , as well simply go in for a queenside fianchetto after all.     We should also add that while this sub-variation has been relatively topical at fairly high levels of late, whereas the elite are happy in both Queen's Gambit Accepted and Declined waters, many club and internet opponents will not be. } )
5. a6
6. e4{ Preparing to disturb Black with  e4 - e5  and White may also now build a fairly big centre with  d2 - d4 . }
6. c5
7. d4{ Seizing further space, while giving White the options of  Be3  and  d4 - d5 , as play enters a sideline of the Queen's Gambit Accepted. }
7. b5
8. Bb3{ Staying on the  a2 - g8  diagonal and now Black must watch out for not just  e4 - e5 , but potential sacrificial blows on  e6 . }
8. cxd4
9. Nxd4{ White is developing fairly quickly and now ready to continue doing so with  Be3  and 0-0, as well as to annoy Black, if allowed, with  e4 - e5 . }
9. Nbd7
10. Be3
10. Bb4
11. Bxe6( { A strong and thematic blow, if one which White either missed or rejected as he went }11.O-O { in Keymer-Sarana, Reykjavik 2021. } )( { Instead, we grab a pawn, introduce the threat of   }12.Bxf7+! Kxf7 13.Qb3 { and Black would have to be fairly brave to take the piece. } )
11. fxe6
12. Nxe6
12. Qa5
13. O-O{ Black might be a piece up here, but that knight on  e6  is a real octopus and White is just doing very well with both  Bd4  and  Nxg7 + followed by  Nf5  high on the agenda, with  Nd5  another way to cause Black a significant headache. }
13. Bxc3
14. bxc3{ Now an invasion with  Qd6  becomes a concern for Black on top of  Nxg7 + ideas. }
14. Bb7
15. Nxg7+
15. Kf8
16. Nf5{ With both  Qd6 + and  Bh6 + threatened and the bishop on  b7  potentially loose, the attack should be a decisive one. }
