[Black "QGD: 4...Nbd7 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. e6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { A familiar method of development from how we met the Slav.    Here too we activate the knight before going  b2-b3  }{ ( }4.b3 c5 { isn't such a bad version of a Tarrasch for Black). } )( { Now   }4...c6 5.b3 { would, of course, take play back into the realm of the Semi-Slav sidelines  and here we'll focus our coverage on: }( 4...c5  )( 4...dxc4  )( 4...a6  )( 4...Nbd7  )( 4...Be7  ){ A couple of minor options should also be briefly mentioned. } )
4. Nbd7
5. b3{ Consistent and logical play as we begin the fianchetto. }
5. Bd6
6. Bb2( { It's not yet a threat, but Black might now begin to fear issues of  Nb5  and }6...c6 7.Qc2 { would take play back into the Slav 6... Nbd7  lines.  } )
6. O-O
7. Qc2( { Our favourite square for the queen, still angling for a transposition to anti-Slav waters with }7...c6 8.Be2 { , }{ while introducing the threat of  cxd5  and  Nb5 , hunting down the bishop-pair. } )
7. a6
8. Be2( { White has tested a fair number of options against this set-up recommended by Sielecki, but }8.g4 Nxg4 9.Rg1 Nde5! { and }{   }8.Rg1!? dxc4 9.bxc4 b5!? { appears to be holding up well enough for Black, as he points out.     Instead, we make a useful developing move while keeping open the options of both  O-O  and more aggressive plans associated with a quick  g2 - g4 . } )
8. Re8
9. g4{ Going for it as White again plays to undermine the defender of  d5 . }
9. e5
10. cxd5{ A consistent move, as well as one which rules out any annoying ideas with ... d4 . }
10. e4
11. Nd4{ The position isn't especially clear, but we would not be too unhappy as White with  g4 - g5  then  O-O-O  very much the plan. }
