5. b3{ Our favourite approach, fianchettoing the queen's bishop and always enabling White after  ...dxc4  to maintain control of  d5  with  bxc4 . Now play may yet enter the waters of the  4...Be7  lines  after }( 5...Be7 6.Bb2 { , }{ although Black can also try something a little more creative. } )
5. c5
6. cxd5{ Our standard reaction to an early ... c5 , planning to hit back in the centre with  d2 - d4  and so saddle Black with an isolated queen's pawn. }
6. exd5
7. d4{ We've transposed to yet another line of the Tarrasch, one where Black has invested a tempo to prevent  Bb5 +, but White cannot be too unhappy when  Bb2 ,  Be2  and  O-O  will harmoniously continue development. }
7. Nc6
8. Bb2
8. Bg4
9. dxc5( { Here this exchange doesn't come with tempo, but is fairly essential if we want to saddle Black with the only IQP on the board, something which is not the case after }9.Be2 Bxf3 10.Bxf3 cxd4 11.exd4 { . } )
9. Bxc5
10. Be2{ Naturally White is happy to break the pin and so prepare to castle. }
10. O-O
11. O-O
11. Qd6
12. h3( { It makes decent sense to put the question to the bishop and now White will be able to look towards a fairly favourable piece exchange and ideas of  Nf5  after }12...Bh5 13.Nh4! { . } )
12. Bxf3
13. Bxf3
13. Rad8
14. Ne2{ Black wasn't doing too badly here in Mekhitarian-Isajevsky, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022, but White's bishop on  f3  was far from a bad piece. Both  Rc1  and  Ng3  are on their way or even  Rc1 ,  g2 - g3  (avoiding any potential issues down the  h2 - b8  diagonal), and  Nf4 . }
