5. b3{ Once a neglected backwater, this has been a pretty topical line of the Reti in recent years thanks to the patronage of Duda, Keymer and Vladislav Artemiev, as well as whole host of the 2700 Club giving it some occasional patronage.     White continues to hold back on  d2 - d4 , while preparing to bring the dark-squared bishop to the long diagonal. Now Black usually continues in typical QGD fashion by castling, although that's by no means forced. }
5. O-O
6. Bb2{ Completing the fianchetto and now Black usually goes in for one of his own or reacts in the centre. As such we'll have a final divide between: }( 6...c5  )( 6...b6  )( 6...dxc4  )
6. dxc4
7. bxc4{ The more ambitious recapture and White may now, if allowed, simply expand in the centre with  d2 - d4  and  Bd3 . }
7. c5
8. Qc2( { Placing the queen on its favourite square, although Grischuk once went }8.Rg1!? { without delay and there also can't be too much wrong with }8.Be2 Nc6 9.O-O { . } )
8. Nc6
9. a3{ It rarely hurts to keep Black out of  b4 , even if White may want to follow up with  Be2  not  Bd3 . }
9. b6
10. Be2{ The best square for the bishop, ensuring that the knight will be secure if White now arranges  g2 - g4 . Incidentally, it should be said that if Black now does something strange, White may even be able to go into full-speed-ahead mode with  Ng5   h6 ;  h4 . }
10. Bb7
11. Rg1( { White is determined to involve the g-pawn after all, although it should be pointed out that Tal, admittedly during one of his more solid phases, was happy just to go }11.O-O Rc8 12.Rad1 { here }{ . } )
11. a6
12. g4{ Thematic and quite effective expansion. }
12. Nd7
13. g5{ Now  h4 - h5  is very much one idea,  Ne4  another. }
13. f5
14. gxf6{ Preventing Black from sealing up the kingside. }
14. Bxf6
15. O-O-O{ With  Rg3  and  Rdg1  on their way, either before or after  Ne4 , White retained the safer king and the upper hand in Rakhmanov-Shuvalova, Cheboksary 2021. }
