4. Be7
5. b3{ Once a neglected backwater, this has been a pretty topical line of the Reti in recent years thanks to the patronage of Duda, Keymer and Vladislav Artemiev, as well as whole host of the 2700 Club giving it some occasional patronage.     White continues to hold back on  d2 - d4 , while preparing to bring the dark-squared bishop to the long diagonal. Now Black usually continues in typical QGD fashion by castling, although that's by no means forced. }
5. O-O
6. Bb2{ Completing the fianchetto and now Black usually goes in for one of his own or reacts in the centre. As such we'll have a final divide between: }( 6...c5  )( 6...b6  )( 6...dxc4  )
6. c5
7. cxd5{ This should seem pretty standard by now, bringing the bishop on  b2  a bit more into play while angling for a position where Black has an IQP. }
7. exd5
8. d4{ A thematic central break, as White introduces ideas of a timely  dxc5 . }
8. Nc6
9. Be2{ Simple chess, as now ... Bg4  won't create a pin. White is also all set to castle, will still recapture on  d4  with the knight if needed and while Black has tried a wide array of moves here, he is yet to demonstrate a route to equality. }
9. cxd4
10. Nxd4{ The ideal recapture and Black should probably now play to challenge on  d4 . }
10. Bc5
11. Nxc6{ Avoiding an exchange on  d4  and ensuring that Black will still be saddled with some weaknesses on the queenside. }
11. bxc6
12. O-O
12. Bd6
13. Rc1{ With the king safe and ideas of both  Na4  and  Qd4 , White was slightly better in Howell-McPhillips, UK Blitz Championship, Solihull 2018. }
