8. d4( { Staking a central foothold after all ahead of completing development with  Bd3  and  O-O . White can also remain flexible with }8.Rc1 Bb7 9.Be2 { , }{ but it's a bit hard to believe in }8.Rg1?! c5 { here when the centre is opening much faster than White would wish. } )
8. Bb7
9. Bd3{ All is now set for  O-O , while Black faces a decision: to play ... c5  or not and, if so, with the queen's knight on  d7  or not? }
9. c5
10. O-O
10. Nbd7
11. Rc1{ Keymer's recent preference in this Queen's Indian-type position, improving the rook, while keeping open the options of both  Ne5  and  Ne2 - g3 . }
11. Rc8
12. Qe2{ With Black's queen slightly struggling for air, it makes sense to hurry the queen's rook across to  d1  and White may also now look to loosen the black queenside defences a little with a timely  Ba6 . }( { We should add that there's also nothing wrong with }12.Ne2 { here if you prefer such an approach. } )
12. Re8
13. Ba6{ White would now be fairly happy if the queen got to take up an active role on  a6 . }
13. Qc7
14. Rfd1{ Black was very solid here, but still a touch worse in Chiburdanidze-Gunina, Batumi (blitz) 2012, where  Bb5  followed by  Ne5  or  Na4  was one way for White to increase the pressure,  Nh4 - f5 , possibly in conjunction with  h2 - h3 , another. }
