[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Slav: Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Intro: Slav & Semi-Slav"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. e3{ We move on to examine a solid and also pretty popular response from Black, who defends  d5  in Slav fashion. However, White most certainly doesn't have to go  d2 - d4  and transpose to the main lines of the Slav.     Instead, we'll hold back on  d4 , usually going  Nc3  in conjunction with placing either the b-pawn or queen on  b3  (the queen will usually be quite happy on  c2  if  b2 - b3  and  Bb2  is played).     The resulting set-ups are most certainly not without sting and it should come as no surprise that this anti-Slav line has quite the pedigree, with a great number of 2700+ grandmasters having deployed it at one stage or another, not least on a number of occasions Levon Aronian, Alexander Grischuk and Vasil Ivanchuk. }( { Here Black opts for typical Slav development with }3...Nf6 { at least 90% of the time, and our coverage divides: }{    }{ ♟️Alternatives to 3... Nf6  }( { ♟️  }4...a6 { - Chebanenko } )( { ♟️  }4...g6 { - Schlecter } )( { ♟️  }4...Bf5 { or }{   }4...Bg4 { - Traditional bishop development } )( { ♟️Unique lines with   }4...Nbd7 { and 5... e5  }( { ♟️Offbeat development after   }4...e6  )( { ♟️Mainlines after   }4...e6  ) ) )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Slav: Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Slav: 3...Bf5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3( { We'll begin this section by examining what to do if Black delays the standard }3...Nf6 { . } )( { Of the three major alternatives }{ ( }3...dxc4 4.Bxc4 { is extremely rare, largely because Black is likely to then have to go ... c5 , thereby leaving him a tempo down on the Reti anti-QGA lines.) }{ ,   }3...e6 { echoes the so-called Triangle ( }{   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 { (or 3.  Nf3 ) }3...c6 { ), and doesn't prevent Black from following up with ... Nf6  after all. } )
3. Bf5
4. cxd5( { A handy exchange to remember to include before going  Qb3 . As }4...Qxd5?! 5.Nc3 { would now cost time and central control, the pawn recapture is invariably seen. } )
4. cxd5
5. Qb3{ With pressure against  b7  and  d5 . We just need to make sure we don't blunder the bishop on  c1  and game away! }
5. Qc7
6. Nc3{ Straightforwardly blocking the c-file, while creating the threat of  Nxd5 , as White also gains the option of  Nb5 , as well as  Bb5 +, developing quickly. }
6. e6
7. Bb5+( { White's simplest option, aiming to cause early problems down the  a4-e8  diagonal }{ ( }7.Nb5!? Qb6 8.Nbd4! { also gives White good chances for a lasting edge) . } )
7. Nd7
8. Bxd7+
8. Qxd7
9. Ne5{ With 10.  Qa4 + to follow, Black is going to have to move his king after all and White has seized a handy early initiative. }
