[White "15) Slav: Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Slav: 3...e6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3( { We'll begin this section by examining what to do if Black delays the standard }3...Nf6 { . } )( { Of the three major alternatives }{ ( }3...dxc4 4.Bxc4 { is extremely rare, largely because Black is likely to then have to go ... c5 , thereby leaving him a tempo down on the Reti anti-QGA lines.) }{ ,   }3...e6 { echoes the so-called Triangle ( }{   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 { (or 3.  Nf3 ) }3...c6 { ), and doesn't prevent Black from following up with ... Nf6  after all. } )
3. e6
4. b3{ Holding back on  Nc3  lest Black is now tempted to switch to a Stonewall formation. }( { In any case, White is able to go  Bb2  and  Qc2  before playing  Nc3 . Objectively Black should now go }4...Nf6 { after all when }5.Bb2 Nbd7 6.Nc3 { transposes to the main line with 4... e6 . } )
4. f5
5. Bb2{ Consistently placing the bishop on a pretty fine diagonal ahead of switching the queen into play. }
5. Nf6
6. Qc2
6. Bd6
7. Be2{ Facilitating castle and continuing to remain flexible while holding back on  Nc3 . }
7. O-O
8. O-O{ Black's Stonewall set-up isn't overly scary when White hasn't gone  d2 - d4 .     Indeed, White will be in control of the key  e4 -square after  d2 - d3  and  Nbd2 , with  Be5 , to swap off Black's better bishop, very much a possibility too. }
8. Nbd7
9. Nd4{ Mikhail Gurevich's creative and fairly strong idea threatened  Nxe6  and gave White an edge in Gurevich-Christenson, Cappelle-la-Grande 2000. The pressure against  f5  means that Black cannot advance with ... e5  and meanwhile White is set to compete for control of  e5  while closing down a potentially problematic diagonal with  f2 - f4 .     The knight may then drop back to  f3 , although it's also tempting to keep it on  d4 . Note too that the pressure against  f5  means White is ready to exchange on  d5 , forcing Black to take back with the c-pawn after which  Nc3 - b5  would be one way to whip up an initiative and begin to exploit the open c-file. }
