[White "16) Slav: Chebanenko 4...a6"]
[Black "Slav: 5...g6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. a6
5. Qc2( 5.b3 { is slightly more popular, but we're quite happy preventing ... Bf5  with the text move, which wasn't covered in Cyrus Lakdawala's  The Slav: Move by Move . White only now wants to go  b2 - b3  and  Bb2 .     Black can force through ... Bf5  with 5... g6 , but how many Chebanenko (... a6  Slav) players also have the Schlechter in their repertoire, especially at club and internet chess? At a high level though, 5...  g6  is likely to be seen instead of the seemingly consistent 5... b5 .     Here we'll split our coverage up into: }( 5...g6  )( 5...e6  )( 5...Bg4  )( 5...b5  ){ That just leaves the slightly misguided exchange on  c4 : } )
5. g6
6. d4( { This change of pace may come as a surprise to Black as we head into Chebanenko waters after all, albeit not one of the very main lines of that fascinating system. After }6.b3 Bg7 7.Bb2 O-O { Black just looks to be quite comfortable and enjoys a pretty secure kingside, so why not follow in the footsteps of Ivanchuk, Mamedyarov and Nepomniachtchi with 6.  d4 !?     White will follow up with  Bd3  and  O-O  and may still go  b2 - b3  and  Bb2 , which will help in the battle for control of  e5 . Now Black usually completes the fianchetto, but that is, of course, far from forced. } )
6. Bf5
7. Bd3{ The simplest policy, aiming to remove Black's most active piece while regaining control of  e4 . }
7. Bxd3
8. Qxd3
8. b5
9. cxd5( { We prefer this to }9.b3 { here, as White looks to quickly exploit the resulting open c-file and aim to show Black's ... b5  advance up as a weakening one. The resulting positions are quite pleasant, but if you want to cut down on the workload, do just go }9.b3 { , }{ which transposes to a position  we'll examine after }{   }6...b5 7.b3 Bf5 8.Bd3 Bxd3 9.Qxd3 { . } )
9. cxd5
10. Bd2{ Now White is ready to meet ... b4  with  Na4 , as well as to bring a rook to  c1 , most likely the king's rook after  O-O  and  Rfc1  }
10. e6
11. O-O
11. Be7
12. Rfc1{ Mission completed.     White now has three useful mini-plans which may be combined in some order: doubling rooks with  Rc1  and  Rac1 ; expansion while eyeing  c6  through  Ne5 ; and probing with  a2 - a4   b4 ;  Ne2 , after which the knight can swing around to a fine spot on  b3  after  Nc1 . }
12. Qd7
13. a4( { Here the undermining thrust is even stronger than }13.Ne5 { , }{ as was seen in Grigorian-Smeets, German League 2022, and now Black must try to keep the position closed, not open up the queenside to benefit White's pieces. } )
13. b4
14. Na2{ The knight does usually retreat to  e2 , but it can also access  c1  from  a2  and here the extra pressure against  b4  is rather useful. }
14. a5
15. Ne5{ White is clearly better, expanding with tempo and being ready to go  Qb5 (+). }
15. Qb7
16. Qb5+{ Anyhow! }
16. Qxb5
17. axb5{ Suddenly  Nxb4  is a threat and one which Black lacks any real defence to. }
17. b3
18. Rc8+
18. Bd8
19. Nc1{ The pawn on  b3  is falling and  Rxa5  also quite the threat. In short, Black has suffered a complete opening disaster. }
