6. d4( { This change of pace may come as a surprise to Black as we head into Chebanenko waters after all, albeit not one of the very main lines of that fascinating system. After }6.b3 Bg7 7.Bb2 O-O { Black just looks to be quite comfortable and enjoys a pretty secure kingside, so why not follow in the footsteps of Ivanchuk, Mamedyarov and Nepomniachtchi with 6.  d4 !?     White will follow up with  Bd3  and  O-O  and may still go  b2 - b3  and  Bb2 , which will help in the battle for control of  e5 . Now Black usually completes the fianchetto, but that is, of course, far from forced. } )
6. Bf5
7. Bd3{ The simplest policy, aiming to remove Black's most active piece while regaining control of  e4 . }
7. Bxd3
8. Qxd3
8. Bg7
9. O-O
9. O-O
10. e4( { It's also quite possible to play slowly here with, say, }10.b3 { , }{ but opening up the centre is tempting when we can hope to exert some pressure down the e-file and keep Black a little bottled up. } )
10. dxe4
11. Nxe4
11. Nxe4
12. Qxe4{ Here  Re1  very much remains on the agenda and the bishop may come out to  g5  (f4 is also a decent post), pressuring  e7 . If White can leave Black tied down to  e7  and unable to satisfactorily break with ... c5  or ... e5  then he may well become rather passive quite quickly. }
12. Nd7
13. Bf4{ Taking control of  e5  while preparing to centralise the rooks to  e1  and  d1 . }
13. Re8
14. Rfe1
14. c5
15. Be5( { A radical idea, but Black should be quite comfortable after }15.d5 b5! { . Instead, White plays to exchange on  g7 , looking to follow up with  d4 - d5  or by creating some pressure down the d-file. } )
15. Nxe5
16. dxe5{ The point of White's play. The bishop on  g7  is rather blunted, ... Qb6  can always be met by  b2 - b3  and whereas Black is a little low on counterplay, White will be able to expand with  h4 - h5 . }
