2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. a6
5. Qc2( 5.b3 { is slightly more popular, but we're quite happy preventing ... Bf5  with the text move, which wasn't covered in Cyrus Lakdawala's  The Slav: Move by Move . White only now wants to go  b2 - b3  and  Bb2 .     Black can force through ... Bf5  with 5... g6 , but how many Chebanenko (... a6  Slav) players also have the Schlechter in their repertoire, especially at club and internet chess? At a high level though, 5...  g6  is likely to be seen instead of the seemingly consistent 5... b5 .     Here we'll split our coverage up into: }( 5...g6  )( 5...e6  )( 5...Bg4  )( 5...b5  ){ That just leaves the slightly misguided exchange on  c4 : } )
5. g6
6. d4( { This change of pace may come as a surprise to Black as we head into Chebanenko waters after all, albeit not one of the very main lines of that fascinating system. After }6.b3 Bg7 7.Bb2 O-O { Black just looks to be quite comfortable and enjoys a pretty secure kingside, so why not follow in the footsteps of Ivanchuk, Mamedyarov and Nepomniachtchi with 6.  d4 !?     White will follow up with  Bd3  and  O-O  and may still go  b2 - b3  and  Bb2 , which will help in the battle for control of  e5 . Now Black usually completes the fianchetto, but that is, of course, far from forced. } )
6. Bg7
7. Bd3{ Now Black's bishop is unlikely to emerge on  f5 , unless he really wants to concede control of the centre after ... dxc4 ;  Bxc4  and  e3 - e4 . }
7. Bg4
8. Ne5{ Leaping forwards with an eye to bagging the bishop-pair, as well as obtaining some pressure with  Qb3 . }
8. Be6
9. c5{ A powerful advance, highlighting the hole on  b6  and clamping down on Black's pawn breaks (... e5  and especially ... c5  are off the table for now, and ... b6  would be quite weakening). }( { White is all set to take full control with  O-O ,  Bd2  and  f2-f4 . Note too that }9...O-O { might now be well met by }10.Na4 { or just }10.O-O { , }{  transposing  to }{   }7...O-O 8.O-O Bg4 9.Ne5 Be6 10.c5 { . } )
9. Nbd7
10. Nxd7( { Once again, we can do even better than }10.f4 { and highlight the slight congestion in Black's position. Now }10...Nxd7 11.O-O { would transpose  to }{   }9...Nfd7 10.Nxd7 Nxd7 11.O-O { . } )
10. Qxd7
11. Na4{ A powerful follow-up, wasting no time exploiting the hole on  b6 . }
11. Rb8
12. Nb6
12. Qd8
13. Bd2{ The bishop may wander on to  c3  to help control  e5  as we also hint at ideas of  Ba5  and  b2 - b4 . }
13. Nd7
14. Na4{ Keeping pieces on and Black tied up left White clearly for choice in Bocharov-Volkov, Taganrog 2019, where after  O-O  and  f2 - f4  he regrouped with  Bd2 - e1 - h4  and gradually took over on the kingside with  g2 - g4 .     Note too how the bishop on  d2  prevents Black from countering on the queenside: }
14. b6
15. cxb6
15. Nxb6
16. Ba5{ White is winning the exchange. }
