6. c5
7. Bb2( { The most complex option, retaining the tension, preparing to continue with   }8.cxd5 exd5 9.Be2 { , }{ and not fearing ... d4 . } )
7. Nc6
8. cxd5( { It's wise to exchange or at least }8.a3 d4 { would appear to be pushing the creative boat out a little too far. } )
8. exd5
9. Rc1{ Ensuring that the rook will be active in the event of any ... Nb4 ;  Qb1  insertion. White also gets ready to unfurl the fianchettoed bishop with  Ne2 - g3  or ideally  Na4 . }
9. Be7
10. Na4{ Taking full advantage of his line-up on the c-file to go straight for the throat on  c5 . }
10. b6
11. Bxf6( { White settled for }11.Be2 { in Izoria-Iskusnyh, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, but this exchange is much stronger as it transpires that  c5  is still vulnerable. } )
11. Bxf6
12. d4{ The point behind the unstereotyped exchange on  f6 . All of a sudden Black finds himself under pressure down the c-file and having to give up a pawn on  c5 , since advancing the knight only serves to make matters worse. }
12. Nb4
13. Qd2{ Renewing the threat on  c5  while beginning to undermine the knight on  b4  so leaves White clearly for choice. }
