5. Qc2( 5.b3 { is slightly more popular, but we're quite happy preventing ... Bf5  with the text move, which wasn't covered in Cyrus Lakdawala's  The Slav: Move by Move . White only now wants to go  b2 - b3  and  Bb2 .     Black can force through ... Bf5  with 5... g6 , but how many Chebanenko (... a6  Slav) players also have the Schlechter in their repertoire, especially at club and internet chess? At a high level though, 5...  g6  is likely to be seen instead of the seemingly consistent 5... b5 .     Here we'll split our coverage up into: }( 5...g6  )( 5...e6  )( 5...Bg4  )( 5...b5  ){ That just leaves the slightly misguided exchange on  c4 : } )
5. b5
6. b3( { Shoring up  c4  while preparing to fianchetto. White is also ready to meet }6...Bg4 { with our favourite }7.Ne5 { leap and }6...g6!? 7.d4 ( 7.Bb2 Bf5 8.Bd3 { is also tempting here with Black having already potentially weakened his position with ... b5 ) was covered via a }{   }5...g6 6.d4 b5 7.b3 { move order in the 5... g6  lines .     That all just leaves a standard Chebanenko method of development for us to consider. } ) )
6. e6
7. Bb2{ Positioning the bishop on a fine diagonal. White may now continue simply with  Be2  and  O-O , but he may do better to clamp down in the centre with  d2 - d4  and can even consider ideas with  g2 - g4 , making good use of the fianchettoed bishop's gaze towards  g7 . }
7. Be7
8. g4{ Even with the bishop on  e7 , this is a strong and even positionally well-justified advance. White simply wants to place Black under unpleasant early pressure with  g4 - g5 . }
8. h6
9. Rg1{ Shoring up the g-pawn while intending to get back on the front foot on the kingside with  h2 - h4  and  g4 - g5 . }
9. g5
10. h4{ Consistently angling to open lines. }
10. gxh4
11. cxd5( { A well-timed exchange and even stronger choice than the }11.Ne5 { followed by  f2 - f4  of O'Gorman-Wadsworth, London 2022. } )
11. cxd5
12. g5{ Consistently bludgeoning away... }
12. hxg5
13. Nxg5{ As now White threatens to crash through with  Nxf7  followed by  Qg6 +. }
13. Rf8
14. Ne2{ Unfurling the bishop on  b2  while preparing to increase the pressure with  Nf4 . Black will then have to watch out for sacrificial breakthroughs on  e6 , as well as White going  Bd3  and  Nxf7 . }
