2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. Be2( { Almost all the top guys go }5.d4 { here, happy to transpose straight into the Schlechter Slav, a solid line for Black which is also considered to give White a definite edge.     You too may be happy to transpose, but we can also hold back on  d2 - d4  and keep Black guessing for a few moves. It's also possible, after first housing the king, to deny Black any ... Bg4  options with an early  h2 - h3 . } )
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. Bg4
7. cxd5{ A timely exchange, eliminating any ... dxc4  ideas before swinging the queen out to  b3 , aiming to exploit the main downside to the early ... Bg4 , the undefended  b7  point. }
7. Nxd5
8. h3{ Asking the question of the bishop before looking to expand in the centre, ideally with both  d2 - d4  and  e3 - e4 , resulting in a type of Grünfeld where Black finds himself low on counterplay. }
8. Bxf3
9. Bxf3{ Threatening to take on  d5  then win a pawn with  Qb3 . }
9. Nxc3
10. bxc3
10. O-O
11. Rb1{ Probing against  b7 . White enjoys a pleasant edge with the two bishops and especially the unopposed light-squared one. Expansion with  d2 - d4  then  a2 - a4  is on the cards, after which  Ba3  and/or  a4 - a5 - a6  may well increase the pressure yet further. }
