1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. Be2( { Almost all the top guys go }5.d4 { here, happy to transpose straight into the Schlechter Slav, a solid line for Black which is also considered to give White a definite edge.     You too may be happy to transpose, but we can also hold back on  d2 - d4  and keep Black guessing for a few moves. It's also possible, after first housing the king, to deny Black any ... Bg4  options with an early  h2 - h3 . } )
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. h3( { Here too White usually goes into the main line of the Schlechter with }7.d4 { when two of Black's main responses are }7...Bg4 { and }7...dxc4 8.Bxc4 Bg4 { . As such, it's tempting to deny Schlechter players their ... Bg4  option, as the Russian GM Maksim Chigaev has liked to do.     That done, we will contest the centre after all with  d2 - d4  and retain definite chances of obtaining a small but pleasant edge thanks to our greater central and slightly easier development. In the limited practice with 7.  h3 , Black has most commonly hurled his knight forwards in a slightly unexpected bid for counterplay. } )
7. a6
8. d4{ Heading directly into a line of the Schlechter while refusing to fear any queenside expansion from Black. }
8. dxc4
9. a4{ Dissuading ... b5  due to the potential pin on the a-file. White only wishes to recapture on  c4  on his terms and is even happy to sacrifice a pawn with central expansion through  e3 - e4  now high on the agenda: }
9. c5
10. d5( { This looks even stronger than the }10.Bxc4 { of Lautier-Renet, Clichy 2001, as White simply prepares to go  Bxc4  and  e3 - e4 . } )
10. e6
11. e4{ Maintaining the important bridgehead on  d5 . }
11. exd5
12. exd5
12. Ne8
13. Re1{ Activating the rook and again we're quite happy to remain a pawn down for a few moves. }
13. Nd6
14. Bf4{ Delroy is blockaded for now, but that's the end of the good news for Black. White is all set to go  Qd2  and  Ne5 , in contrast to which it's far from easy for Black to untangle his queenside, since White will always be able to consider  g2 - g4  if a bishop appears on  f5 . }
