[White "18) Slav: The Traditional 4...Bf5 / 4...Bg4"]
[Black "Slav: 4...Bf5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3{ We'll begin our coverage of the main line (3... Nf6 ) by examining a very natural Slav move, deploying the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, which is a fairly popular choice in club and internet chess. }
4. Bf5
5. cxd5( { Consistent with our policy in the rare 3rd moves lines  that was   }3...Bf5 4.cxd5 cxd5 5.Qb3 { . White exchanges in the centre before swinging the queen out to  b3 . } )
5. Nxd5
6. d3( { Reti-like play as White prepares  e3-e4  now that an exchange on  c3  won't be a problem in return. A transposition to a Slav with }6.d4 { should also yield quite a pleasant edge, as may even }6.Qb3 Qb6 7.Bc4 { , }{ but we'd prefer to keep pieces on and our d-pawn away from  d4 , for now. } )
6. e6
7. e4{ Consistent, as well as effective. }
7. Nxc3
8. bxc3
8. Bg6
9. Qb3{ Having sidelined Black's light-squared bishop, we pressure his weakest spot,  b7 .     White has ideas too of hunting down the bishop-pair with  Ne5 , ideas which may even be combined with a disruptive  h2 - h4  advance, and the dark-squared bishop will be deployed to attack Black's queen with tempo, should the chance arise: }
9. Qc7
10. Bf4{ A strong sacrifice as taking would cost Black his rook in the corner. }
10. Qb6
11. Nd2{ The knight heads for  c4  as White aims to force an exchange on  b3 , after which the pressure down the resulting half-open a-file may be quite useful indeed. Black is already clearly worse, lacking central control and counterplay, and with a sidelined bishop. }
