2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3{ We'll begin our coverage of the main line (3... Nf6 ) by examining a very natural Slav move, deploying the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, which is a fairly popular choice in club and internet chess. }
4. Bf5
5. cxd5( { Consistent with our policy in the rare 3rd moves lines  that was   }3...Bf5 4.cxd5 cxd5 5.Qb3 { . White exchanges in the centre before swinging the queen out to  b3 . } )
5. cxd5
6. Qb3{ Pressuring not just  b7 , but also  d5  and Black should probably now swallow his pride and return his bishop to base. }
6. Nc6
7. Qxb7{ There goes a pawn! This sacrifice is playable for Black when White has gone  d2 - d4  instead of  Nf3 , but here it is unconvincing so long as White follows up actively. }
7. Bd7
8. Nb5( { Much stronger than the }8.Qb3 { of Burmakin-Arjun, Montcada 2012, as White creates a big threat on  c7  to force the black rook away from heading to  b8 . } )
8. Rc8
9. Nxa7( { Calmly claiming a second pawn and with tempo, as if }9...Rc7 { there's }10.Nxc6 { . } )
9. Nxa7
10. Qxa7
10. e6
11. Ne5{ Eyeing the bishop-pair as White keeps up the pressure. The queen will make it back via either  a6  or  d4 . }
11. Bc5
12. Qa6
12. O-O
13. Be2{ There's no rush to exchange on  d7  as the bishop isn't exactly running away. As well as that potential trade, White is now ready to castle and also drop the queen back to  d3 . Black does have a lead in development, but surely nothing like enough for two pawns. }
