6. Qb3{ Pressuring not just  b7 , but also  d5  and Black should probably now swallow his pride and return his bishop to base. }
6. Bc8
7. Bb5+( { Angling to stay in Reti waters }{ ( }7.d4 { would again be a line of the Slav), while putting White's superior development to use. } )
7. Nc6
8. e4( { A brand new idea, or so we believe, and one which may jolt your opponent out of their chair! The established alternative is }8.Ne5 { to increase the pressure, and if }8...Bd7 { to grind away with the two bishops after }9.Nxd7 Qxd7 10.d4 { . We've by no means given up on getting in  Ne5 , but first want to offer Black a number of tempting but misguided moves in the centre. } )
8. e6
9. d3( { Maintaining a strongpoint on  e4  makes it harder for Black to acquire counterplay than }9.e5 Ne4 { does, and now }{   }9...a6 10.Bxc6+ bxc6 11.O-O { would return us to a position we considered via an 8... a6  move order. } )
9. Bd7
10. exd5{ Accepting the offer before Black gets in a challenge with ... a6 . }
10. exd5
11. O-O{ Wisely housing the king rather than grab the pawn and allow a check on the  e1 - a5  diagonal. Now though  Nxd5  is a threat, as is  Re1 +. }
11. d4
12. Ng5{ With a certain threat as White suddenly gains a very strong initiative indeed. }
12. Qe7
13. Nce4{ With  Re1  next up, Black is simply in huge trouble. }
