1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3{ We now come on to a line with a fair pedigree, having been used in such high-profile games as Topalov-Anand, Khanty-Mansiysk Candidates 2014, but which has never entirely taken off at lower levels. }( { That's likely because most club and internet Slav players prefer the traditional Slav lines ( ...Bf5 ), rather than the Semi-Slav to which   }4...Nbd7 { angles for a transposition after }5.d4 e6 { . } )
4. Nbd7
5. Qc2( { Consistent with our approach against  4...e6 , and now }5...e6 6.b3 Bd6 7.Bb2 { would transpose to there. Yes, with 5.  Qc2  we are allowing Black to expand centrally, but there's an important point that Black won't be able to set up a perfect pawn centre. } )( { The alternative is   }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.d4 { , }{ angling to show that Black's knight is slightly misplaced in an Exchange Slav structure. } )
5. e5
6. cxd5{ An important follow-up to 5.  Qc2  as we hope that Black will allow an early and rather strong invasion on  b5 . }
6. cxd5
7. Nb5{ Black simply lacks a good way to cover  c7 . }
7. Nc5
8. Nxe5
8. a6
9. Nd4{ A fine spot for the knight, contesting the  e6 - and  f5 -squares. White will drop the  e5 -knight back to  f3  if attacked and wants to continue development with  Be2 ,  O-O  and  d2 - d3 , which should leave Black struggling for compensation. }
