[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Slav: The Ambitious 4...Nbd7 / 5...e5"]
[Black "Slav: 6...Nxd5 / 7...Nb4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3{ We now come on to a line with a fair pedigree, having been used in such high-profile games as Topalov-Anand, Khanty-Mansiysk Candidates 2014, but which has never entirely taken off at lower levels. }( { That's likely because most club and internet Slav players prefer the traditional Slav lines ( ...Bf5 ), rather than the Semi-Slav to which   }4...Nbd7 { angles for a transposition after }5.d4 e6 { . } )
4. Nbd7
5. Qc2( { Consistent with our approach against  4...e6 , and now }5...e6 6.b3 Bd6 7.Bb2 { would transpose to there. Yes, with 5.  Qc2  we are allowing Black to expand centrally, but there's an important point that Black won't be able to set up a perfect pawn centre. } )( { The alternative is   }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.d4 { , }{ angling to show that Black's knight is slightly misplaced in an Exchange Slav structure. } )
5. e5
6. cxd5{ An important follow-up to 5.  Qc2  as we hope that Black will allow an early and rather strong invasion on  b5 . }
6. Nxd5
7. d4( { Fighting for central control so is far from forced }{ ( }7.Bc4!? { being one sensible alternative), and now Black must be careful not to allow White too much early activity or the superior structure (after exchanges on  d5  and  e5 ). } )
7. Nb4
8. Qd2{ Perhaps not the most obvious spot for the queen but a good one as the dark-squared bishop is going to be fianchettoed, and the alternatives have also been tested, but a good choice.     As well as threatening  dxe5  and  a2 - a3 , White will now bring the dark-squared bishop to the long diagonal after  b2 - b3  or  b2 - b4 . }
8. exd4
9. Nxd4( { Activating the knight while avoiding taking on an IQP and, of course, }9.Qxd4?? Nc2+ { would not be wise. } )
9. Nb6
10. a3{ Kicking the knight back before ... c5  becomes slightly awkward. }
10. N4d5
11. b3{ Keeping full control of  c4 , in contrast to which 11.b4 looked a little weakening in Kovchan-Matlakov, European Individual Championship, Batumi 2018. }
11. Be7
12. Bb2
12. O-O
13. Bd3{ Black is very solid and should objectively be OK here, but White should certainly not be dispirited. The immediate idea is 14.  Qc2  to tickle the black kingside, the king will be quite safe on the kingside and after R(a)d1 White may be quick to activate with  Ne4  or  Nf5 . }
