5. Qc2( { Consistent with our approach against  4...e6 , and now }5...e6 6.b3 Bd6 7.Bb2 { would transpose to there. Yes, with 5.  Qc2  we are allowing Black to expand centrally, but there's an important point that Black won't be able to set up a perfect pawn centre. } )( { The alternative is   }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.d4 { , }{ angling to show that Black's knight is slightly misplaced in an Exchange Slav structure. } )
5. e5
6. cxd5{ An important follow-up to 5.  Qc2  as we hope that Black will allow an early and rather strong invasion on  b5 . }
6. Nxd5
7. d4( { Fighting for central control so is far from forced }{ ( }7.Bc4!? { being one sensible alternative), and now Black must be careful not to allow White too much early activity or the superior structure (after exchanges on  d5  and  e5 ). } )
7. Bd6
8. dxe5{ Taking up the challenge. This simple approach might work well at sub-grandmaster level. }
8. Nxe5
9. Nxe5
9. Bxe5
10. Qe4{ Now Black only has one way to avoid losing a piece and it's a move which entails a pawn sacrifice. }
10. Qe7
11. Nxd5
11. cxd5
12. Bb5+{ Preventing Black from castling ahead of bagging the pawn on  d5 . }
12. Kf8
13. Qxd5
13. g6
14. Bd2{ Offering to return the pawn for the initiative, while also preparing to contest the long diagonal with  Bc3 . }
14. Kg7
15. Qxe5+{ Forcing some handy simplification. }
15. Qxe5
16. Bc3
16. Qxc3+
17. bxc3
17. Be6
18. Ke2{ Keeping the king in the centre as it's an endgame.  Rfc1  will follow to cover the c-pawn and White can look to involve the other rook after  a2 - a4 .     Black did manage to hold in both Topalov-Anand, Khanty-Mansiysk 2014, and Bauer-Ragger, Austrian League 2015, and while the position should, indeed, be a draw, White is a pawn up and it's not hard to imagine a Magnus Carlsen or a Keith Arkell grinding out a win from here. }
