[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Semi-Slav: 4...e6 - Offbeat Development"]
[Black "Semi-Slav: 5...Bd6 / 6...b6 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3( { Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, }1.Nf3 { is the most reliable way to achieve it. } )
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. e6
5. b3( { Beginning a queenside fianchetto is a good policy against this most dynamic of the various ways Black can handle the Slav, namely a Semi-Slav policy. Of course, }5.d4 { would transpose to the famous Meran variation, but we don't need to obstruct the long diagonal and after  Bb2  may continue development with  Qc2  then  Be2  or even push the g-pawn two squares! } )
5. Bd6
6. Bb2( { Completing the fianchetto and now Black's main moves are to castle or to continue development with }6...Nbd7 { . }{ As such, we'll undertake a further divide with: }( 6...Nbd7  )( 6...O-O  ){ (On the odd occasion, Black may also contemplate something else, of which the immediate central advance doesn't look especially wise and fianchettoing on the queenside may only encourage White to expand aggressively on the kingside.) } )
6. b6
7. Qc2{ White hints at timely exchange on  d5 , while keeping both  d2 - d4  and  g2 - g4  available. }
7. O-O
8. Be2
8. Bb7
9. Rg1( { It should be said that there's absolutely nothing wrong with }9.d4 { then  O-O , but getting the rook off the long diagonal while preparing to strike with  g2 - g4 - g5  may seem more attractive to those of an attacking disposition. } )
9. c5
10. g4( { White wastes no time putting Black under some pressure with the g-pawn and may now meet }10...Nc6 { with the sensible, bishop-preserving }11.a3 { . } )
10. Nbd7
11. g5{ Now Harry too is set to advance, unless Black makes the misguided decision to head forwards. }
11. Ne4
12. cxd5{ An important exchange to flick in ahead of weakening Black further with a trade on  e4 . }
12. exd5
13. Nxe4
13. dxe4
14. Qc3{ The star point to White's play as mate is already threatened and Black forced to weaken. }
14. f6
15. gxf6{ Naturally White is happy to open up lines and involve the rook on  g1 . }
15. Rxf6
16. Bc4+{ The prelude not so much to  Ng5  as a stunning queen sacrifice! }
16. Kh8
17. Qxf6( { As the pawn is pinned, White may now even meet }17...gxf6 { with the material-regaining }18.Ng5 { . } )
17. Nxf6
18. Ng5{ Black doesn't have to return the queen here, but is simply in some trouble regardless. }
18. Qe7
19. Nf7+
19. Kg8
20. Nxd6+{ Everything continues to come with tempo. }
20. Kf8
21. Nf5{ Taking on  g7  next will leave White with material equality and still a rather sizeable initiative. }
