1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. e6
5. b3( { Beginning a queenside fianchetto is a good policy against this most dynamic of the various ways Black can handle the Slav, namely a Semi-Slav policy. Of course, }5.d4 { would transpose to the famous Meran variation, but we don't need to obstruct the long diagonal and after  Bb2  may continue development with  Qc2  then  Be2  or even push the g-pawn two squares! } )
5. Bd6
6. Bb2( { Completing the fianchetto and now Black's main moves are to castle or to continue development with }6...Nbd7 { . }{ As such, we'll undertake a further divide with: }( 6...Nbd7  )( 6...O-O  ){ (On the odd occasion, Black may also contemplate something else, of which the immediate central advance doesn't look especially wise and fianchettoing on the queenside may only encourage White to expand aggressively on the kingside.) } )
6. b6
7. Qc2{ White hints at timely exchange on  d5 , while keeping both  d2 - d4  and  g2 - g4  available. }
7. O-O
8. Be2
8. Bb7
9. Rg1( { It should be said that there's absolutely nothing wrong with }9.d4 { then  O-O , but getting the rook off the long diagonal while preparing to strike with  g2 - g4 - g5  may seem more attractive to those of an attacking disposition. } )
9. Na6
10. g4{ As ... Nb4  can for now be met by  Qb1  and with the bishop safely back on  e2 , not  d3 , White is able to continue his plans on the kingside. }
10. e5
11. a3( { Sensibly keeping  ...Nb4  ideas and Black's counterplay under control (note further that   }9...e5 10.g4 Na6 11.a3 { would also lead to this position). }{ With  g4 - g5  and  h3 - h4  on their way White definitely has some attacking chances in this unclear position, which, of course, the engines assess as '0.00'.     It still appears to have only had the one test, despite being briefly analysed by Sam Shankland when he endorsed it for Black in his largely excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: Black vs the English, Reti and sidelines' course. } )
11. Nc7
12. g5{ It's hard to believe that there can be a better plan for White here than involving Gary and Harry to the maximum. }
12. Nd7
13. h4
13. Qe7
14. h5( { Ploughing straight ahead and hoping to follow up with  Nh4-f5 , although you may also have fun analysing }14.Bd3!? { , }{ a tricky move and one designed against Shankland's general defensive concept of ... f5  (he stopped the specific analysis at 13... Qe7 , noting that White could no longer safely castle queenside). After }{   }14.Bd3 e4 15.Nxe4 dxe4 16.Bxe4 { White certainly has reasonable looking attacking chances and compensation for the piece. } )
14. f5
15. gxf6
15. Rxf6
16. Nh4( { Having opened the g-file, White gets to activate the knight after all and this is a better way to do so than the }16.Ng5 Nf8 { of Hilby-Mishra, Charlotte 2021. Both  Nf5  and  Bd3  are now definite threats and while the engines still display '0.00', we suspect that many human opponents would struggle here to reopen the long diagonal for the bishop on  b2 . } )
16. e4
17. h6
17. g6
18. d3( { Angling to collapse Black's centre or reinvolve the light-squared bishop after }18...exd3? 19.Bxd3 { . } )( { The board is on fire, but it does seem that an extremely booked-up opponent might be OK here with precise play: }18...Rxf2! 19.Nxg6! hxg6 20.Rxg6+ { The engines' top line, causing serious havoc to the black king ahead of opening the centre and ideally castling long at the right minute. }Kf8 21.dxe4! Ne5! 22.exd5!? { Throwing more wood on to the fire as White aims to involve his queen, while now  Kxf2  is finally a threat as is  h6 - h7 . }Nxg6 23.Qxg6 Rf6! 24.h7! { The sacrifices just keep on coming! }Rxg6 25.h8=Q+ { White is still a rook down and Black's king still very exposed. }Rg8 26.Qh6+ Ke8 27.O-O-O { Remarkably or not, we're still in the realm of '0.00'. White now threatens to take on  c6  then  d6 , and also has ideas involving  Ne4 . }cxd5 28.Ne4! Qxe4 29.Qxd6 Qxe3+ 30.Rd2 { This is probably a good time to stop. We just hope that someone gets to test and enjoy playing this line as White at some point and will only note for now that }30...Rg5 { preventing the mating check on  h5 , is seemingly the only move that maintains the rough balance. } )
