[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3( { Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, }1.Nf3 { is the most reliable way to achieve it. } )
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. e6
5. b3( { Beginning a queenside fianchetto is a good policy against this most dynamic of the various ways Black can handle the Slav, namely a Semi-Slav policy. Of course, }5.d4 { would transpose to the famous Meran variation, but we don't need to obstruct the long diagonal and after  Bb2  may continue development with  Qc2  then  Be2  or even push the g-pawn two squares! } )
5. Bd6
6. Bb2( { Completing the fianchetto and now Black's main moves are to castle or to continue development with }6...Nbd7 { . }{ As such, we'll undertake a further divide with: }( 6...Nbd7  )( 6...O-O  ){ (On the odd occasion, Black may also contemplate something else, of which the immediate central advance doesn't look especially wise and fianchettoing on the queenside may only encourage White to expand aggressively on the kingside.) } )
6. e5
7. cxd5{ A change of approach, but a well-timed one as White switches to picking up the bishop-pair with  Nb5 . }
7. cxd5
8. Nb5{ Attacking  e5 , as well as  d6 . }
8. Nc6
9. Nxd6+
9. Qxd6
10. a4( { A sneaky-engine approved move and a good alternative to }10.Bb5 e4 11.Nd4 { . White simply intends to discombobulate with  Ba3 . } )
10. Bg4
11. Ba3( { Consistent and preparing to annoy Black further with }11...Nb4 12.Bb5+ { . } )
11. Qe6
12. h3{ White angles for a second bishop and enjoys a pleasant edge with Black unable to castle. }
12. Bh5
13. Rc1( { Even stronger than }13.Be2 { , as White would like to be fairly aggressive here, looking to get in at least two of  g3 - g4 ,  Bb5  and  d2 - d4 . } )
13. e4
14. g4{ Breaking the pin and happy to offer a pawn to open up the position to White's advantage. }
14. Bg6
15. Rxc6( { A wonderful engine-inspired idea, although the simple }15.Nd4 { is also quite promising. } )( { Now   }15...Qxc6?? 16.Bb5 { would, of course, not be wise for Black. } )
15. bxc6
16. Nd4{ With tempo. White will pick off  c6  and enjoy excellent play for the exchange, with Black's king trapped in the centre and ideas of both  Bb5 (+) and squeezing on the kingside beginning with  h3 - h4 . }
