7. Be2( { Here before  Qc2 . Why? Well, quite simply Black's active approach with }7.Qc2 e5! { (as endorsed, perhaps unsurprisingly, by Sam Shankland on his  Lifetime Repertoires: Black vs the English, Reti and sidelines  course) }8.cxd5 cxd5 9.Nb5 Nc6 10.Nxd6 Qxd6 { with ideas of ... Nb4  and ... d4  offers him more counterplay than ideal. } )( { As such, White develops the bishop first and will next go  Qc2  unless Black still reacts in the centre with   }7...e5 { . Note too that }{   }7...b6 8.Qc2 Bb7 { can now be met by }9.Rg1!? { , }{ as we've already seen via a }{   }6...b6 7.Qc2 O-O 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Rg1 {  move order.  } )
7. a6
8. d4{ The bishop might be on  e2  rather than  d3  here, but it still makes sense to compete for control of those important central squares,  e5  and  c5 .     Now ... c5  will not only cost Black a tempo, but will result in an isolated queen's pawn after exchanges on  c5  and  d5 . }
8. Nbd7
9. O-O
9. b5
10. Qc2{ Still a good spot for the queen, offering some potential support to  c4  while facilitating  Rfd1  and the  e3 - e4  break. }
10. Bb7
11. c5{ A strong advance, hampering Black's attempts to liberate his position with ... c5 . }
11. Bc7
12. b4{ Continuing to seize space, hoping to get in  a2 - a4  and all the while refusing to fear Black's central counter. }
12. e5
13. dxe5
13. Nxe5
14. Nxe5( { A simple strategy, although }14.e4!? { is also pretty tempting and strong. } )
14. Bxe5
15. Bd3{ This left White with a very pleasant advantage in Dautov-Müller, Bremen 1998, where he was always able to shore up  b4  with  a2 - a3 , if needed, and was also set to exploit his superior bishops after  Rae1  and  f2 - f4 .     And note that the Greek Gift isn't on, since White can run up the board and also has strong counter-pressure against  h7 . }
15. Bxh2+
16. Kxh2
16. Ng4+
17. Kg3{ White will frustrate the black queen with  f2 - f4  if needed and is all set to strike with  Bxh7 + and  Rh1 . }
