12. Nxe4( { A new try, not without practical sting and one which might just stun an opponent. We should definitely avoid }12.Rxg4? exf3 { when ...  Ne5  is coming, but }{   }12.Nd4 Nge5 13.cxd5 { is by no means impossible. } )
12. dxe4
13. Qxe4( { The tactics work for White, as after }13...Nge5 14.Nxe5 { there's always  f2 - f4  if needed, while }{   }13...f5? { fails to }14.Qe6+ { . } )
13. Nxh2
14. Nxh2
14. Bxh2
15. Rh1{ You'll see worse line-ups down the h-file from a white perspective! }
15. Qxg5
16. O-O-O( { Dodging Black's cheapo and }16...Nf6 17.Qe7! { would be a pretty strong invasion, but will an opponent now find the only way to defend with the clock ticking? } )
16. Nc5
17. Qf3( { As retreating the bishop will walk slap back into  18. Rdg1  or }17...Be5 18.d4 { , }{ White is regaining the piece and while Black may be OK, he still needs to be the more careful. } )( { For example:   }17...Qf5 18.Rxh2 Qxf3 19.Bxf3 Bf5 20.Rg1!? { Continuing to complicate to the maximum. }20...Nd3+ 21.Kb1 { There isn't yet a good discovered check ( }21...Ne5+? { fails to }22.e4 { ), and White can always go  Ka1  next if needed. With a handy central majority on top of the kingside pressure, White can very much aim to grind away. } )
