11. bxc4{ Establishing decent central control yet again. }
11. e5
12. h3( { White avoids any potential issues on  h2 , can now meet }12...e4? { with }13.Ng5 { and is ready to improve the pieces with  Rad1  and  Bd3 . } )
12. exd4
13. exd4
13. Nf8
14. Rfe1{ Placing the rook on the open file left White with a fairly pleasant pull in Nevednichy-Bulmaga, Avoine 2015, in part because Black was a little low on counterplay. White may now go  Bd3  then  Ne4 , which also offers an exchange of pieces as we look to bring the potential power of the bishop on  b2  into play.     Ideally White will land up attacking on the kingside and/or carrying out a powerful and effective advance in  d4 - d5 . }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) Semi-Slav: Theoretical 8th Move Mainlines"]
[Black "Semi-Slav: 8...Re8 #9"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. e6
5. b3( { Beginning a queenside fianchetto is a good policy against this most dynamic of the various ways Black can handle the Slav, namely a Semi-Slav policy. Of course, }5.d4 { would transpose to the famous Meran variation, but we don't need to obstruct the long diagonal and after  Bb2  may continue development with  Qc2  then  Be2  or even push the g-pawn two squares! } )
5. Bd6
6. Bb2( { Completing the fianchetto and now Black's main moves are to castle or to continue development with }6...Nbd7 { . }{ As such, we'll undertake a further divide with: }( 6...Nbd7  )( 6...O-O  ){ (On the odd occasion, Black may also contemplate something else, of which the immediate central advance doesn't look especially wise and fianchettoing on the queenside may only encourage White to expand aggressively on the kingside.) } )
6. O-O
7. Be2( { Here before  Qc2 . Why? Well, quite simply Black's active approach with }7.Qc2 e5! { (as endorsed, perhaps unsurprisingly, by Sam Shankland on his  Lifetime Repertoires: Black vs the English, Reti and sidelines  course) }8.cxd5 cxd5 9.Nb5 Nc6 10.Nxd6 Qxd6 { with ideas of ... Nb4  and ... d4  offers him more counterplay than ideal. } )( { As such, White develops the bishop first and will next go  Qc2  unless Black still reacts in the centre with   }7...e5 { . Note too that }{   }7...b6 8.Qc2 Bb7 { can now be met by }9.Rg1!? { , }{ as we've already seen via a }{   }6...b6 7.Qc2 O-O 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Rg1 {  move order.  } )
7. Nbd7
8. Qc2{ Bringing the queen to its favourite square ahead of castling, expanding with  d2 - d4  or undertaking something more aggressive with the g-pawn.     In this theoretical tabiya Black has quite a wide choice and we have another divide: }( 8...e5  )( 8...dxc4  )( 8...b6  )( 8...a6  )( 8...Qe7  )( 8...Re8  ){ These are listed and presented in very rough order of importance, with the last three the options usually chosen by theoretical types. We will cover those in the final chapter. }
8. Re8
9. O-O( { Remaining flexible in the centre, if not the prelude to a direct attack. Unfortunately after  8...Re8  White lacks a good, aggressive continuation: }9.Rg1?! e5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.Ne4 N7f6! { reveals the problem when Black is developing central counterplay too quickly. } )( { Despite some effort, we were also unable to make   }9.g4?! Nxg4 10.Rg1 Ngf6 { work, hence the calm text move. We make the king quite safe without committing to anything specific in the centre, thereby keeping options of both  d2 - d4  and  cxd5  open, while provoking Black to expand himself. } )( { Here Black might go   }9...Qe7 { after all when we saw }10.d4 { via a an }{   }8...Qe7 9.O-O Re8 10.d4 {  move order in the 8... Qe7  lines.  } )
9. Qc7
10. Rac1{ A sneaky move as White threatens to exchange on  d5  then go  Nb5 . }
10. Ne5
11. Nxe5
11. Bxe5
12. f4{ Powerful expansion and an advance which should certainly delight that fine bishop on  b2 . }
12. Bd6
13. cxd5( { Simple chess as White plays to obtain the bishop-pair and dark-square control after }13...exd5 14.Nb5 { . } )
13. Nxd5
14. Ne4{ Black was already in serious trouble in Keymer-Aditya, Internet (rapid) 2021, where White was not only intending to take on  d6 , but to begin a strong attack with  Rf3 - g3 . }
