9. O-O( { Remaining flexible in the centre, if not the prelude to a direct attack. Unfortunately after  8...Re8  White lacks a good, aggressive continuation: }9.Rg1?! e5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.Ne4 N7f6! { reveals the problem when Black is developing central counterplay too quickly. } )( { Despite some effort, we were also unable to make   }9.g4?! Nxg4 10.Rg1 Ngf6 { work, hence the calm text move. We make the king quite safe without committing to anything specific in the centre, thereby keeping options of both  d2 - d4  and  cxd5  open, while provoking Black to expand himself. } )( { Here Black might go   }9...Qe7 { after all when we saw }10.d4 { via a an }{   }8...Qe7 9.O-O Re8 10.d4 {  move order in the 8... Qe7  lines.  } )
9. e5
10. cxd5{ Naturally we have no design to allow Black to dominate the centre and would now like to get in our favourite  Nb5  raid. }
10. Nxd5
11. Ne4{ A very thematic way to activate both this knight and the bishop on  b2 . }
11. Bc7
12. Ng3{ Alexander Grischuk's choice, taking control of  f5 . White enjoys a fairly pleasant reversed Sicilian position where opening up the centre with  d2 - d4  is one plan, queenside expansion through  a2 - a3  and  b3 - b4  another. }
12. Nf8
13. a3{ Now White would quite like to obtain some queenside pressure with  b3 - b4  then  Rac1  and may also break with  d2 - d4 , having kept Black out of  b4 . }
13. a5
14. d4{ Seizing the initiative by threatening to take on  e5 . }
14. Ng6
15. Bd3{ And now Black must be careful not to shed a pawn on  e5  or  h7 . }
15. exd4
16. Nxd4{ This left White with the more active pieces and a very pleasant edge in Grischuk-Kramnik, Wijk aan Zee 2011, no less, where White was all set to increase the pressure with  Rad1  and  Bf5 . }
