6. Nc3
6. Be7
7. Bd3{ A good square for the bishop, supporting  e4  and already angling for a potential kingside attack. }
7. O-O{ Arguably a case of castling into it, but it's already impossible for Black to come close to equalising, which is no surprise considering the slightly sad state of his queenside pieces. }( {  A.  }7...Bd7 8.O-O Nc8?! { is a rather strange regrouping. Euwe's predecessor and successor as world champion showed how to deal with it: }9.Qb3 b6 10.Bf4 Nc6 11.Rfd1 Nd6 12.Rac1 Na5 13.Qc2 { This left White well centralised, with much the better coordination and already a huge advantage in Alekhine-Blanco Sanjuan, France (simul) 1923. There White was already threatening to crash through with 14.  d5  or 14.  e5  and then 15.  d5 . } )( {  B.  }7...c5!? 8.dxc5 { A simple reaction and one which doesn't help Black to liberate his bishop on  c8 , as 8.  d5  might. }8...N6d7!? ( 8...Bxc5 9.O-O O-O 10.e5! { This echoes our main game to begin an attack. } )9.O-O Nxc5 10.Be2 Qxd1 11.Rxd1 O-O 12.Be3 { The queens might be off, but that's the end of the good news for Black, with White all set to drive back his only active piece with  b2 - b4 . Then  a2 - a3  and  Rac1  will leave White in control of the position and set to begin to probe, such as with  Nb5 . } )
8. O-O{ Our coverage of this sideline ends here in the theory section , as there are natural attacking ideas involving  Qe2  and eventually  e5  with a kingside attack. }
8. c5
9. dxc5{ Again this is a simple and strong method of dealing with the central challenge. }
9. Bxc5{ Euwe is quick to whip up a powerful attack after this. }( 9...N6d7!? 10.Qe2 Nxc5 11.Bc2 { Even here White is clearly for choice, with  e4 - e5  very much still on the agenda, as well as  Rfd1  to annoy the black queen. } )
