28. Qh5( 28...Qf6 29.Nxc6! 29...Qxc6 30.Qe5 Rd8 31.Rg1 31...g6 32.Bb2 Rg8 33.Rg5! { The threat of  Rxf5  is a killer. } )( 28...Nxd3 29.Qd2! Bxd4 30.Qxd3 { White is just doing extremely well, since Black will be mated if he touches the rook: }30...Bxa1? 31.Bxd5+  )
29. Rg1{ Threatening to crash through on  g7  and not worrying about the potentially loose rook on  e2 . }
29. Bxd4
30. Qxd4
30. Qxf3+
31. Rg2
31. Qxe2
32. Qxg7+{ The main point of White's play, finally breaking through to the black king. }
32. Ke8
33. Bxd5
33. cxd5( 33...Nxd5? 34.Qf8+ Kd7 35.Rg7+ Ke6 36.Qd6  )( 33...Qf1+!? 34.Rg1 Qxg1+ 35.Kxg1 Nxd5 36.Qf8+ Kd7 37.Qd6+ Kc8 38.Qxc6+ Nc7 39.Bd6 { The extra queen is just too powerful. } )
34. h3{ Black has a move and an extra rook, but there's just no defence to White's threats which include the slow-motion  Qxh7  and  Rg8 #. }( 34.h3 Qxd3 ( 34...Qe7 35.Qd4! { The threat of 36.  Rg8 + and 37.  Rg7  is surprisingly hard to stop. } )35.Qf6! ( 35.Qxh7? Qe4! 36.Kg1 Qe1+ 37.Kh2 Qe5+  )Qxh3+ 36.Kg1 { Threatening to check with the rook on  g8  then  g7 . }36...Qxg2+ 37.Kxg2 { Even here the extra queen is just far too strong, especially with Black's knight unable to move and pieces vulnerable to various tactical ideas, the simplest being 38.  Bxb4   Rxb4  39.  Qc6 +, forking. } )
