1. Nf3{ Although our setup (the Reti Proper) can transpose from other first moves, 1.  Nf3  is the most reliable way to achieve it. }
1. d5
2. c4{ We waste no time challenging Black's early presence in the centre. }
2. dxc4
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Bxc4
4. e6
5. O-O{ Move order is fairly interchangeable around here, but the immediate fianchetto with }( 5.b3 { is our preferred route when }5...a6 6.Bb2 c5 7.O-O { would transpose to the game. } )
5. a6( 5...c5 6.b3 Nc6 7.Bb2 Be7 8.Be2 O-O { This is Black's most solid and probably best approach when }9.d3!? { is our recommendation in the calm 3.e3 mainlines , intending to develop the queenside à la Grivas with  Nbd2 ,  a2 - a3 ,  Qc2  and  Rac1 . }{ Just as when Black has a pawn on  a6 , }( 9.d4 { is the alternative, intending to grind away with slightly the better bishops after }9...cxd4 10.Nxd4 Nxd4 11.Bxd4 { and  Bf3  }( { or }11.Qxd4 { then  Bf3 . } ) ) )
6. b3
6. c5
7. Bb2
7. Nc6{ Black is alert and holds back on queenside expansion: }( 7...b5 8.Be2 Bb7 9.a4! { The upcoming hole on  c4  gives White a small but pleasant edge, as we've seen. } )
8. Be2{ Retreating away from any attack and thereby preparing the way for  d2 - d3 . }
8. Be7
9. d3( { Deviating from our main recommendation in the calm  3.e3  mainline. }9.d4 cxd4 10.Nxd4 { White has a small but pleasant edge thanks to enjoying the superior bishops and with  Bf3  very much on the way. } )
9. O-O
10. Nbd2{ Completing minor piece development. Next White will rule out any annoying ... Nb4  raid with  a2 - a3  ahead of tidying up the queenside with  Qc2  and  Rac1 . }
10. b6
11. a3
11. Bb7
12. Qc2
12. Rc8
13. Rac1{ Completing the mini-plan. White has a reversed Hedgehog or reversed Scheveningen set-up if you prefer. Black should be OK and has a pretty solid set-up, but doesn't have an especially obvious plan, in contrast to which White can consider the very Reti-like  Qb1  and  Qa1 . Note too that in an ideal world, White will one day break out with a well-timed  b3 - b4  or  d3 - d4 . }
13. Nd5{ Centralisation. }( 13...Qc7!? 14.Qb1 Qb8 { Black copied White thus in the later game Berkes-Karjakin, Moscow 2005, which it's worth seeing a few more moves of: }15.Qa1 Rfd8 16.Rfd1 Ne8 17.Nc4!? { With a threat as Black is lured forwards. }17...b5 18.Ncd2! ( 18.Nce5?! Na5! { Suddenly Black has a clear target and easy counterplay. } )Qa7 19.Rc2 { This prepared to double rooks, with  Ne4  another way to increase the pressure on  c5 . With the  d3 - d4  break always on the cards too, White's position is probably slightly the easier to play, solid and objectively OK though Black is and indeed the 'Minister of Defence' did eventually hold the draw. } )
14. Rfd1{ A useful move, while there's no point in rushing the queen to  a1  if Black might be about to offer an exchange of dark-squared bishops. }
14. Bd6( 14...Bf6!? 15.Ne4 Bxb2 16.Qxb2 { Grivas assessed this as slightly better for White in his notes in 'Chess Informant 53'. The engines don't agree, but once again we have a position where many would struggle as Black who lacks a obvious and active plan, since forcing through ... e5  and/or ... f5  will create weaknesses. Meanwhile Black must keep an eye on the  b3 - b4  break and White can manoeuvre, the Berkesesque  Rc2  and  Rdc1  being one plan,  Bf1 ,  g2 - g3  and  Bg2  another to activate the bishop and contest the long diagonal. } )
15. Bf1{ Heading for  g2  and Grivas actually also has other designs for the  e2 -square. }
15. Bb8{ The Greek Grandmaster wasn't especially impressed with this move as it becomes clear that Velikov is struggling to find a good plan (... Qc7  is hardly about to inconvenience the white king). }
16. Nc4
16. Nde7( 16...b5!? 17.Qe2! { A neat point, although so long as Black doesn't exchange here he may still be OK, despite the weakened  c5  point. }17...bxc4? 18.dxc4 Qe7 19.cxd5 exd5 20.Rxd5! { Yes, White doesn't even need to be content to manoeuvre and gradually target the hanging pawns, but can fall in with Black's plans: }20...Nd4! 21.Nxd4 Bxd5 22.Nf5 22...Qc7 23.f4 { With  g7  under severe pressure, White enjoys excellent compensation for the exchange. } )
17. Qe2{ The point of White's play. The bishop is en route to  g2  and with the white rook vis-à-vis the opposition queen,  d3 - d4  may open lines faster than Black would like. }
17. Nf5( 17...Re8?! 18.d4! { A timely and powerful break-out. }18...cxd4?! ( 18...Qc7! 19.g3! b5 20.Nce5 { With  Bg2  on the way, the more active pieces and pressure down the c-file, White definitely enjoys a pleasant edge. } )19.Nxd4 19...Qc7 20.f4! { Even stronger than fianchettoing as White clamps down on the  e5 -square. The simple plan is now to make good use of the fine bishop on  g2  by beginning to target the black kingside with  Qg4 . } )
18. g3{ With Black having trained his forces on  d4 , White switches to plan B, improving the light-squared bishop. }
18. b5{ Black can't resist breaking out, despite the target this creates for White on  c5 . }( 18...f6?! { Grivas's suggested improvement, but it turns out that White has a strong idea here: }19.d4! cxd4 20.e4! { Driving one knight away from  d4  ahead of going  Nxd4  with pressure down the central files and against  b6 . } )
19. Ncd2
19. Qb6
20. Bg2{ Continuing his mini-plan and the next one is very likely to be to increase the pressure against  c5  through the rooks and  Ne4 . }
20. Rfd8
21. Rc2
21. Nce7( 21...Bd6!? 22.Ne4 Bf8 { This looks like a more solid defence, but even here White can consider some aggressive ideas: }23.g4 { and even }( 23.Nfg5!? h6 24.Qh5! { , intending }24...hxg5 25.Nxg5 Nh6 26.Be4 { with a big attack and two large threats in  Qxh6  and  Nxf7 . } ) )
22. Rdc1
22. Ng6
23. e4{ Grivas was pretty happy with this move, but it didn't actually have to drive Black backwards. }( 23.Ne4! Bd6 ( 23...Bxe4?! 24.dxe4 Nfe7 25.a4!? { White is doing very well with the two bishops and strong options to squeeze on both flanks with  Bf1  and  h2 - h4 - h5 . } )24.h4 { All of a sudden White is expanding with tempo on the kingside and Black undoubtedly under some pressure. } )
23. Nfe7( 23...Nd4! 24.Bxd4 ( 24.Nxd4 cxd4 25.f4?! e5! 26.f5 Nf8 { With ... a5  and ... Nd7 - c5  on their way, Black's queenside play is likely stronger than anything White can muster against his king. } )cxd4 25.b4 { This looks very nice for White with  Nb3  imminent, but actually Black may be OK after a precise sequence: }25...Rxc2 26.Rxc2 a5! 27.Nb3 axb4 28.axb4 e5 29.Nc5 Bc8 { The knight on  c5  looks good, but Black is rock solid and should be OK. } )
24. h4{ Here comes Harry! With Black rather tied down and lacking counterplay, Grivas wastes no time seizing the initiative. }
24. Nf8
25. h5{ With White enjoying such a fine bishop on  b2 , Black is now well advised not to allow 26.  h6  when his dark squares would collapse. }
25. h6
26. Nh2{ King's Indian Attack style play as White goes straight after the hook Black has just been forced to create on  h6 . }
26. Qd6( 26...f6! 27.Ng4 e5 28.Ne3 { Black's light squares and kingside are a little vulnerable, but he is very solid here and may well be OK, since the bishop on  b2  is no longer playing an active role. } )
27. Ng4
27. Qxd3{ Completely underestimating the danger. }( 27...Nh7! 28.e5!? ( 28.Nxh6+? gxh6 29.Qg4+ { Tempting, but White will now come up short: }29...Ng5 30.f4 f5!  )Qd7 29.Bxb7 Qxb7 30.Ne4 { Thanks to the bridgehead on  e5  and excellent knight on  e4  White should be slightly better. } )
28. Nxh6+{ Olé! }
28. gxh6
29. Qg4+
29. Neg6
30. hxg6{ Recouping the piece having shattered the black kingside. }
30. Nxg6( 30...fxg6 31.Qh4 e5! 32.Qxh6 { White is, of course, clearly for choice, but at least this way Black would have been clinging on for the time being. } )
31. Bf6{ A superb spot for the bishop as White simply prepares to go after  h6  with  Qh5 . }
31. Kh7
32. Nf3{ Spurning the exchange to threaten not just  Rd2 , but  Ng5 +. There's already just no good defence. }
32. Bd6( 32...c4 33.Ng5+! 33...hxg5? 34.Qh5+ Kg8 35.Qh6 { Mate follows. } )
33. Rd2
33. Qxb3
34. Qh5( 34.Rxd6? Rxd6 35.Ng5+ Kg8! { Black seems to be defending here, but Grivas isn't in a rush and why should he be with such strong pressure down the d-file? } )
34. Bf8
35. Rxd8{ Cashing in. }
35. Rxd8
36. Bxd8
36. c4
37. Bf6
37. Qxa3
38. Rd1{ Those three connected queenside pawns might look strong, but White is a rook ahead and that piece is all set to join in the assault on the black king. }
38. Bc6
39. Rd8{ The threat of  Ng5 + then  Qxh6  is a killer. }
39. c3
40. Ng5+
