[White "Model Games"]
[Black "A. Kevitz vs. M. Schroeder, Manhattan CC Championship, 1955"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
1. d5
2. c4
2. dxc4
3. e4
3. c5
4. Bxc4
4. Nc6
5. b4{ This gambit must have been one of the reasons which first attracted Kevitz's fellow New Yorker George Kramer to trying 5.  b4 .     White attacks  c5  and introduces the idea of  b4 - b5  to challenge the knight on  c6 , and in the very limited practice thus far, Black has tended to decline the pawn, as Schroeder now does. }
5. e6
6. b5( { Consistent. Now }6...Nce7 7.Bb2 { places the dark-squared bishop on a fine, open diagonal, so opponents might well prefer to leap forwards. } )
6. Nd4
7. Nxd4{ Forcing the pace and trying to lure Black into a little trap... }( 7.Bb2!? Nf6 8.d3 { Even here White has a pleasant edge, with the a-pawn set to advance and the queen's knight emerge via  d2 . } )
7. Qxd4( 7...cxd4 8.O-O Nf6 9.d3 { This is a very pleasant edge for White, who may seize further space with both  a2 - a4  and  b2 - b4 .     Note too the options available from  d2  for the knight, who may head to  b3  to pressure  d4 , switch to the kingside via  f3  or even help White seize the initiative with a timely  e4 - e5  and  Ne4 . } )
8. Qc2{ The key follow-up and a move we hope you'd remembered! }
8. Nf6( 8...Qxa1? 9.Bb2 { Black is losing the queen for clearly insufficient compensation. } )
9. d3{ Calmly overprotecting  e4  as the rook remains poisoned. }
9. b6
10. O-O{ One of several good moves for White and, yes, of course, Black still can't really touch the rook. }
10. Bb7( 10...Qxa1? 11.Bb2 Qxb2 12.Qxb2 { White is ahead on material and will still expand with  a2 - a4  and  f2 - f4 , possibly in conjunction with  Nd2 - f3 - e5 . } )
11. Bb2
11. Qd8
12. Nd2{ Having driven the black queen backwards, White completes development and can be delighted with the outcome of the opening.    The bishop on  b2  is an especially good piece and White controls plenty of key squares in the centre and on the queenside.     You can check the theoretical section  for further analysis of similar lines. }
12. Be7
13. f4{ Route one stuff as Kevitz introduces the idea of pressuring  e6  with  f4 - f5 , as well as a timely  e4 - e5  advance. }
13. Ng4( 13...O-O 14.Rae1 a6 { This would definitely have been better for Black than the misguided leap in the game, if still clearly better for White: }15.a4 { White maintains the key cramping point on  b5  and may next look to swing a rook into the attack, ideally via  e3  then  Rg3  or even  Rh3 . } )
14. Rae1{ Prudently covering the  e3 -square while also preparing to swing the queen around towards the kingside, doing so with tempo via  d1 . }
14. Bf6
15. e5{ Blunting the bishop on  b2  is a price well worth paying for such a powerful advance, as well as one which also comes with tempo. Note how fine a square is now available for the knight on  e4 . }
15. Bh4{ Another bishop move and challenge, and also one which is easily rebuffed. }
16. g3
16. Be7
17. h3{ White simply wants to expand on the kingside. This is a decent plan, but there was an even stronger one available, }( 17.Ne4! O-O ( 17...Bxe4?! 18.dxe4! { This would just be positional suicide for Black, who is now potentially vulnerable down the d-file and especially devoid of counterplay. White will simply roll ahead with  h2 - h3  and  f4 - f5 . } )18.f5! exf5 19.Rxf5 { Tony Kosten's recommended improvement for White in his earlier notes to this game. White simply blasts open lines and prepares to take aim at  f7 , with  Qb3  and  Ref1  set to augment the pressure. }19...Kh8 20.Qe2!? Nh6 21.Rh5 { White has spurned the  f7 -pawn to enjoy a huge attack. Already  Rxh6  followed by  Nd6  is very much an idea, bringing the bishop on  b2  fully back into play. } )
17. Nh6
18. g4{ It's important to keep the black knight sidelined. }
18. O-O
19. Ne4
19. Kh8
20. f5{ Having improved his knight, White sees no reason to make any more small improving moves and simply gets on with things, introducing the definite threat of  f5 - f6 . }
20. Bh4( 20...exf5!? 21.gxf5 f6 { This radical defence is how the engines want to prevent  f5 - f6 . It does, however, allow White the pleasant choice between obtaining a protected passed pawn on  e6  and playing for the attack: }22.exf6!? Bxf6 ( 22...gxf6? 23.Qe2 { And the arrival of the queen on  h5 , possibly teamed up with a rook lift via  h4 , spells very bad news for Black. } )23.Nxf6 gxf6 24.Qd2 { Sensibly switching the queen to a dark square, a colour complex on which Black is pretty weak. The queen may emerge via  f4  and the white king will always be safe enough on  h2  if needed.     Meanwhile the rook on  f1  may just step up to  f2  or look to join in the fray via  f3  and  g3  or even  f4  and  h4 . } )
21. Re2
21. Qd7( 21...exf5?! 22.gxf5 Qd7 23.f6!? { One of several tempting and strong moves as White simply wants to go after the black king. }23...gxf6 24.e6! fxe6 25.Rxf6! { Black is going to emerge serious material in arrears due to White's monstrous pressure down the long diagonal and as ... Kg8  or ... Qg7  can always be met by  Rg2 (+). } )
22. f6{ Wasting no time in sticking a fish bone in the black king's throat. }( 22.Qd2! { As pointed out by Tony Kosten, first improving the queen would have been even stronger and only then  f5 - f6  or even  Nf6 . } )
22. Rg8
23. Qc1{ Black's position begins to creak rather loudly on the dark squares and Schroeder now finds himself having to go in for quite a radical defence. }
23. g5
24. Kh2{ There's nothing wrong with calmly improving the king to emphasize White's complete control of the position and keep the black bishop out of  g3 . }( 24.Nd6! { This direct leap would arguably have been even stronger. White simply wants to open lines after  Qe3  with  d3 - d4  (then  Bd3  may even become an option), and need not fear Black activating his dark-squared bishop: }24...Bg3 25.Qe3 Bf4 26.Rxf4! gxf4 27.Qxf4 27...Rg6 28.Kf1! { Black surely isn't going to survive this, with not only  d3 - d4 , but  g4 - g5  followed by  h3 - h4 - h5  high on White's agenda. } )
24. a6
25. a4{ Maintaining the powerful bridgehead on the queenside. }
25. axb5
26. axb5{ The natural recapture. }( 26.Bxb5!? Bc6 27.Nd6 Bxb5 28.axb5 { As shown by the engines, this would also have been very strong, since both black minor pieces are pretty much out of play for good. } )
26. Bd5
27. Nd6{ Finally White leaps forwards so. Now he may well look to open up the position (don't forget that the knight on  h6  and bishop on  h4  aren't playing!), doing so with  d3 - d4  in conjunction with an exchange of bishops on  d5 .     Good advice for Black is already hard to come by, but giving White a passed b-pawn, as he now does, was surely not the sternest defence. }
27. Bxc4
28. Qxc4
28. Rgd8
29. d4
29. Ra7( 29...cxd4 30.Qxd4 30...Rab8 31.Rc2 { This is just winning for White, who is effectively two pieces to the good and all set to double on then invade down the c-file. } )
30. dxc5
30. bxc5
31. b6
31. Ra4
32. Qxc5{ The extra passed pawn on  b6  is looking pretty useful and Black is still rather devoid of any real counterplay. }
32. Ra2
33. Qc7
33. Ra4
34. Rd1
34. Kg8
35. Nf5{ Finishing in style. }( 35.Nxf7! { This would also have done the trick as the rook on  d1  is taboo: }35...Qxd1 36.Nxh6+ Kh8 37.Qg7  )
35. Nxg4+
36. hxg4
36. Qxd1
37. Nh6+{ Forcing mate. }
37. Kh8
38. Nxf7+
38. Kg8
39. Nh6+
