[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2{ An independent anti-Slav line, although play will soon transpose into our coverage. }( 4.Nc3 e6 5.b3 Bd6 6.Bb2 O-O 7.Be2 Nbd7 8.Qc2 { This would, of course, be our route into the position which arises after 8.Be2 in the game. } )
4. e6
5. b3{ The bishop spies a fine diagonal after all. }
5. Bd6
6. Bb2
6. Nbd7
7. Nc3
7. O-O
8. Be2{ Getting back on course and in this game we'll now see a radical reaction in the centre from Black. }
8. dxc4
9. bxc4{ The best way to recapture here, taking firm control of that important central square,  d5 . }
9. e5
10. g4{ We still rather like Cornette's bold advance, looking to seize an early initiative with  g4 - g5  and  Ne4 . It hasn't, however, yet fully caught on. }( 10.O-O Re8 11.d4 { This has been a somewhat more common reaction in practice, as well as an idea we also covered in our theoretical section. White simply challenges in the centre and even has ideas of a timely  Ng5 . } )
10. Nxg4{ The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating! }
11. Ne4{ A powerful follow-up. White activates the knight with tempo. }
11. Bc7( 11...Be7!? 12.Ng3!? { As we've already noted, this should also promise White full compensation with ideas of both  Nf5  and  h2 - h4  high on the agenda. } )
12. Rg1
12. f5( 12...Ngf6 13.Ng3! { Keeping pieces on leaves Black's position looking a little congested and now not only is  Nf5  a decent idea, but so too is that of  h2 - h4  followed by  Ng5 , thereby eyeing the potential mate on  h7 . } )
13. Neg5{ For a second time activating the knight with tempo and, under early pressure, Black now slips up. }
13. Qe7( 13...Ndf6 { Black needed to find this move, although even here White has the initiative and promising compensation. }14.c5! { As we've already noted, this brings the light-squared bishop into play and if Black were to now voluntarily retreat his knight to  h6 , White wouldn't need to spend a move on  h2 - h3 . } )
14. Rxg4{ Ouch and, of course, the rook is taboo due to the potential mate on  h7 .    You can see theoretical coverage of this sac here.  }
14. h6
15. c5{ Calmly leaving two pieces en prise to introduce the threat of  Bc4 +. White may also simply go  O-O-O  and  Rdg1 , and while Black can regain his piece, he will remain under a very heavy attack. }
15. Nf6( 15...hxg5 16.Bc4+ Kh7 17.Nxg5+ Kh6 18.O-O-O { Black surely isn't going to survive, with  Rdg1  followed by  Rh4 + White's most obvious and strongest idea. } )
16. Bc4+
16. Nd5
17. e4{ A tempting advance, but there was much better. }( 17.O-O-O ! hxg5 18.Rxg5 { With  Rdg1  next up then  Nh4 , possibly after first  h2 - h4 - h5 , Black is simply getting crushed. } )
17. fxe4( 17...fxg4? 18.exd5 { The twin threats of mate on  h7  and  d6 + decide proceedings. } )
18. Qxe4
18. Bf5( 18...hxg5? 19.Nxg5 19...Bf5 20.Bxd5+ cxd5 21.Qxd5+ { In view of the potential mate down the h-file, Black is forced into a desperate-looking exchange sacrifice on  f7 . } )
19. Bxd5+
19. Kh8( 19...cxd5!? 20.Qxd5+ Kh8 21.Rh4! { This maintains White's extra piece, but is also how the engines prefer to try and defend as Black. It should not be sufficient though. For example: }21...Rad8 22.Qb3!? Rd3 23.Qc4 { The position is a bit messy, but surely doesn't offer Black enough for a piece. White will either castle long or keep his king on  e1  and activate the queen's rook via  c1  and  c3 . } )
20. Nxe5{ A stunning blow and one which we suspect was overlooked. }
20. Bxe5( 20...Bxe4 21.Nef7+ Rxf7 ( 21...Kg8 22.Nxh6+ Kh8 23.Nhf7+ Kg8 24.Rxe4 { This regains the queen with a huge amount of interest. } )22.Nxf7+ Kg8 23.Rxe4! { Maintaining the pressure down the  a2 - g8  diagonal is even stronger than cashing in by taking on  h6  then  g7 . }23...Qxc5 24.Bb3 Kh7 ( 24...Kf8 25.Rc1 Qh5 26.Ng5! { A neat finish. Mate via either  h7  or  a3  decides matters. } )25.Rc1! Qh5 26.Rc3 { Activating the rook, as demonstrated by Tony Kosten in his notes to this game, should decide matters.     Materially White already has more than enough for the queen and may now begin to go after  g7  following  Rce3  and  Re7 . } )
21. Qxe5
21. Qxe5+( 21...Rae8 22.Qxe7 Rxe7+ 23.Re4! { Another neat resource pointed out by Kosten and spotted by Cornette before he sacrificed his queen. Black can reach an endgame, but not survive: }23...Bxe4 24.Bxe4 hxg5 25.d3 { The white bishops are monsters and Black has much the more vulnerable kingside. } )
22. Bxe5{ It's now two extra pieces and Black can't take everything. }
22. Rae8( 22...cxd5 23.Rh4 { Preserving the extra piece. } )( 22...Bxg4 23.Nf7+ Kh7 24.Be4+ Kg8 25.Nd6 { A superb spot for the knight, controlling  e8 . White may even be able to follow up with  f2 - f4 ,  Kf2  and  Rg1 , and Black surely won't manage to survive. } )
23. d4
